76561198220331643,Recommended,290340,22628519,"Posted: 25 April, 2016",all,FullMetalBucket,"This game is a real treat for those looking for something unique, visually attractive, and challenging. It is very well produced blend of strategy, role playing, and board gaming. The producers have comitted great attention to detail. Every element of the game; characters, story line, events, spells, equipment, flavor text, and even poetry, create a true sense that this is a fully imagined world that you have entered.Before I go into the gameplay, a little bit on the game lore would be helpful: Armello is a kingdom of animal clans ruled by a lion (king). Unfortunately, the king has been infected by a creeping, evil disease called the ""Rot"". It has driven him mad and slowly ebbes his health. Each night the Rot grows in him, and each morning he loses health. His madness is evident in his daily decrees, that create chaos around the realm, affecting the heroes and inhabitants of the kingdom. The time then has come to depose the king and for a new hero to take the throne.Armello is a turn based 4 player board game (you can also play against AI). At the beginning of a game players choose a hero, a female or male character, that is either a bear, wolf, rabbit, or rat. Each character has unique stats (Fight/Body/Wit/Spirit), and also a unique ability. The hero's creature clan type provides a trait that provides a boon for that character as well. From there players select a ring and amulet that provide additional abilities or benefits to their hero.Players take turns drawing cards, moving their heroes about the game board, casting spells, and completing quests. Completing a quest improves hero stats, and rewards them with equipment, followers, or treasures. As heroes adventure they will encounter perils, both randomly placed, and ones placed by other players and the king. They may also attack other players and cast spells on opponents to hinder their progress or even kill them. There are King's guards and evil creatures called banes that wander about the board that will attack players and generally get in the way.The object for each player is to aquire the means to dethrone the king and become the new monarch/matriarch themself. There are 3 ways to win the game; by defeating the king in straight one on one combat, by gathering 4 spirit stones to destroy the ""Rotting"" king, or by having the most prestige points when the king finally succumbs to the Rot after 10 turns.So here's the take away for Armello:Pros:Beautifully imagined and rendered world. From the artwork to the storyline to the general atmosphere, you know that this game was a labor of love for the very competent makers.Unique. Armello borrows from several genres and merges them into new gaming experience that is a welcome break from the copy/paste fodder that has cluttered the online gaming selection.Fun and addictive. Even if you don't win you'll have tons of fun tripping up your opponents and discovering new ways to use heroes, board tactics, and spells.Replayability. The variety in characters, abilities, and win conditions make each match unique and provides tons of replayability. Achievements will unlock new rings and amulets that give players even more opportunities to expirement with heroes and win conditions.Cons:Waiting. Armellos is a turn based game so this may turn some people off. In addition each night and morning there are non-player creatures that must move and decrees to resolve. One consolation is that you can still play spells, perils, and equip items during another players turn.More waiting. The player base is still small and you may have to wait a while, sometimes longer than a while, to get a full group of opponents. (best bet is to invite your friends to a game)Random. ""The best laid plans of mice and men...."". The randomness of card drawing, dice rolls in battle, decrees, and questing, can sometimes wreck your strategy. It can be frustrating since you have little control over this element of the game. But the more you play, the more you learn how to mitigate this factor and/or adust your strategy in midstride.You can't win. Ocassionaly, at some point in an Armello match you'll realize that you can't win. Kinda like in Monopoly when you own Mediterranian and Baltic Avenues and your opponent owns everything else. It just ain't gonna happen. Sometimes as early as midgame you come to this realization. Many online players drop out at this point (the game inserts an AI player to take over when this happens). And you'll feel like your just going through the motions, hopelessly. But, you can still get some enjoyment out of messing with the leading player or even by helping another player steal the win!In closing this is a great game that's different and enjoyable. It deserves to succeed. So get it, play it, and definately tell your family, friends, neighbors, and enemies to give it a try."
,Recommended,290340,29164417,Posted: 10 January,all,✨ Hatty ✨,"*** UPDATE 28/APRIL 2017: Bots still a problem. I'm currently in a game where one person is clicking end turn from the safety of their base. The other two are in a team, so I'm screwed as they target me instead of each other. Have reported people who play unfairly and bot in the past but it seems to do nothing as I still get matched with them. Either botting or teaming up happens about every 4 out of 5 games.Really annoyed by the state of this game as developers seem to ignore it even being an issue because it doesn't happen to them.I still enjoy the game for me personally and there is a single player mode as well.==============old review:I really enjoy this game. I have some cons and pros though which I'll include below.For many years I've followed this, it had a successful kickstarter which brought it to steam.It was quite popular, and I'd say still is, probably. I never have too many issues finding people to play with.PROS:---------- nice music- REALLY GOOD ART- the cards in game have art which are painted and ANIMATED!- the cards in game have bonuses, or curses which you can play on yourself, tiles, or others- NICE >> you can't harrass each other in chat, as the responses are specific to each character. (For example, my rabbit will say 'salutations' instead of just 'hello', where as another may say 'Hiya!' etc., It depends on personality of the playing character. You cannot type to talk. (Maybe a con to some, see below)- Dice are tradeable, easy to get. Just play and it throws boxes/keys at you.- Can play with friends. (also a con, see below)- 8 characters to start, tons of dice, rings to unlock (benefits), cards, and map is completely randomized- Events happen at random in the game which makes for good gameplay.But I have a few complaints, not with the game, as it's quite fun, really balanced and random.But with the community.CONS:==================================- Can't type to talk. This is fine for me for the most part, as I'm less anxious about joining a game knowing I can't be verbally trolled, but at the same time, I wish there was a 'nice dice!' button, or something, I'd really just like them to know that they have nice dice!- Why are you allowed to invite 3 players? I would say a 2v2 or inviting for a full match is okay. But when playing a 3v1, honestly I always feel pressured, a 2v2 would be okay, but a 3v1 is difficult. Whenever I've played against a 3v1, some of them will hunt you down and block you in your base, while letting one other character win the game for them, then they will often give each other reccomendations to level each other up. It's not fun. AT ALL.- Same with above, but instead of hunting you? They go afk. They'll just fill a space and not move from their clan base ( they're immune to attacks there) so theres less players to fight against for their friends and they can farm.- Bot Farming > people will join the game, go afk in the base, and just get chests when the game is finished. You can't even kick them. Some of the items are worth £2+ so it's a big problem. :(**** NOTE Reporting is easy to do. Please report these players. ****You press escape when in game and just click the bug icon on the right corner. I did it there a few times now, but I don't know if pushiments are ever taken."
