76561198017065468,Recommended,290340,25005906,"Posted: 18 August, 2016",all,Jorrrrrn,"Thumbs skyward, ladies and gents.To clarify just what Armello is--it is definitely a boardgame come to life in digital format. The card-drawing, the dice-rolling, the playing field all remind you of those cutting-edge games at the hobby store that nobody's ever heard of. The mechanics of the game are dreadfully simple, so you don't need Coordination Level: Dark Souls to play. If that's OK with you, then play on.I'd also say that this is first and foremost a multiplayer game. Single player had me for about 10 hours, but there's no campaign or complex progression or anything that will drive you to play solo all year. The AI can seem a little tricky at first, but it eventually becomes fairly predictable. At some point, you're gonna wanna branch out and go into the multiplayer queue.The game's simplicity allows even a sub-par connection to keep you hooked up, which means matchmaking can reach farther afield and keeps moving even though the game doesn't have a mega-roster of players. I live in central US, and queue times are about 30sec-2min. On rare occasions when the queue exceeds 5min, the game lets me dabble in single player while waiting and informs me when the match is ready.You've also got one of the best communities I've seen, so it's not hard to find peeps to play/get acquainted with. Chat is restrained to a selection of speech options like you'd see in Hearthstone... At first it unnerved me a little, but then I went 20 straight games without reading a single homophobic slur or N4z1 slogan and I decided that that was OK with me.As important as I feel multiplayer is, I don't think you'll ever suffer from the population problems that crash giant multiplayer-only titles. Low connection requirements, community, and ability to sub in an AI slot in a pinch mean you can always find a game.The one thing that initially drove me nuts about the game is the same things that bothered some other reviewers here: Dat RNG. There were times when I first started playing the game where I didn't just curse fate--I wanted to take all of the kittens in the world and punch each one of them in the face. Yes, I was that angry. But I've come to realize the error of my ways.There are a couple aspects of the game that take getting used to.First--the mechanics... Managing cards and dice rolls can have a subtle but powerful effect on how the game plays out. You have opportunities to affect what kind of dice you roll, how many, and even whether or not the game comes down to a dice duel at all. Waste these and you'll be constantly at the mercy of RNGesus. You can't control the dice--but you CAN influence them an awful lot.The second thing is that there are multiple victory conditions. This, I think, is one of the ways in which the game truly shines. Contrary to the most popular negative review on here, I'd say that your path to victory is NOT obvious in the first few turns. It's constantly changing, and you need to pursue multiple paths simultaneously or make some titanic shift in your favor at just the right moment so that no one can counter you.Get a strong start and someone will pull the rug out from under you. Let someone else draw fire and you might slip in the side door when no one's looking. You have to be flexible and play it loose because you won't even know what the winning combo IS until that perfect moment arrives. Push down one path every time instead of going with the flow = 75% chance of Doom.Lastly, the statistical hurdle: 4 players. You'll lose often enough, because 3 people lose EVERY game. Maybe you can whoop the AI, but against random Interweb goons even a 75% win rate means you're semi-pro. If your sense of self-worth is centered around executing consistent strategies and earning consistent rewards... then Armello may drive you to madness. Get used to feeling like everyone else is trying to drag you down--they are.The devs support their game with multiple weekly events. What's already here is good, but with this support the game also seems to be on a good long-term trajectory.I'd rate Armello as a $30+ game masquerading as a $20 title. Since I can't retroactively pay them $10 I'll probably just buy the new DLC.And the Guppy plushy. Guppy is the next big thing in video game mascots."
76561198086505175,Recommended,290340,22909070,"Posted: 11 May, 2016",all,[POEX]An-Tarxamon,"My overall rating for Armello: 85/100Armello brought us a board-game-like adventure-strategy  where four heroes are racing for the throne of Armello ruled by corrupted king. Strategy here is a key element, though luck factor is also important, as fights are being resolved with dice rolls, but a good player may ensure that odds will be on his or her side. Lets see this title in detail.GAMEPLAY+ Variety of heroes with unique abilities+ Hex tile design+ Day/Night cycle+ Huge replayability+ Four victory options+ Interactive turn-based system+ Cards+ Story-driven prologueo Fair multiplayer (host leave may crash the game)o Luck and random number generator- May be frustrating sometimesGameplay is cute and lovely. Heroes are moving on hex based tile, and trying to get prestige, magic, coins or even rot sometimes. With four modificable stats via quests - Fight, Body, Wits and Spirit - the amount of strategies is huge and also it adds more replayability to Armello.There are basically four victory options. Firstly we have a Prestige victory - gaining prestige for quests, killing heroes and banes. Second one is a Spirit Stone victory, after gaining four stones through quests and stone circles, the king is banished after engaging him. Kingslayer and Rot victory are very simillar, you have to kill the king, survive, when trying for Rot, your Rot has to be higher than king's.Day and night cycle also brings important aspect, as heroes have affinity to day parts and also other creatures too. During the day Guards move, during the night Banes are spawning and moving. It may be an advantage or disadvantage, heroes may also become corrupted, which changes their strategy.Good strategy may bring the odds to player side, yet still luck plays an important factor here and after several unhappy rolls players may get frustrated. It is a risk, that needs to be taken. There are six kinds of cards - Items, Spells, Trickery, that may be drawn, Treasures, Followers, acquirable from dugneons or quests, and Palace cards, which player simply has to encounter. Questing is important, as it may deny the palace perils, which are really difficult and nasty.Multiplayer is fair and it is up to the player, if they decide to team up or not, victory may belong to the best one. Also mechanics are good againts leavers or delaying players, though, when the host drops it might result to game crash.Last addition to good points is a story-driven prologue, that is not just a simple tutorial, but the beginning of story in Armello. Also easy to understand and explain game mechanics.CHARACTERS+ Traits and affinities, variety of themPlayer may choose so far from eight heroes and adjust the strategy accordingly.Rabbit clan is represented by Amber, the Far Seeker, who is excellent in dungeons seeking, thus has a higher chance of get a reward. Another member is Barnaby, the Screwloose, who collects equipment and when changing equipped items, cards are not burned.Bear Clan offers Sana, the Forest Sister, who uses Spirit instead of Fight, when dealing with corrupted creatures, and Bran, the Oakbreaker, who gains temporarily Fight after each successfully casted spell.Rat Clan has Mercurio, the Grinning Blade, who steals gold from previous settlement owners and Zosha, the Whirlwind, who is alwasy stealthed at night and may ambush other creatures.Finally, we have here the Wolf Clan. Thane, the Winter Wolf pierces burned cards with swords through enemy's defense, River, the Howling Arrow, shoots before fight, inflicting one hp injury to target.King is always corrupted, whose healthe decrease and rot increase through the game. Banes get additional rot each night, guards are dealing with them, or with heroes, who have bounty on themselves.New heroes are announced, review will be updated after release.VISUAL+ Nice art style+ Animations+ Dices+ SEASONS- Few graphic glitchesArt style is lovely and suits the nature of the game. Also combat animations with dice rolls are amazing (there are four different dice styles so far with animations), differing whether the dice explodes or not, also hit to the hero differs from a blocked attack. There were some graphic glitches, but very rare and not affecting gameplay.It si good to see, that developers still keep this game changing and alive. Newest addition is about year seasons and it is great. The war of the throne keeps going through the whole year. And nou players have that impresion.SOUNDTRACK+ Stylised+ Lisa Gerrard performance+ Changing accordingly to the atmosphereSoundtrack is very well created and composed. Songs are underlining the dark-fantasy atmosphere and course of the game. Also Lisa Gerrard participated and her voice well known from Dead Can Dance or Gladiator suits melodies and game very well. I am glad that developers released soundtrack, that may be also purchased even by non-early-access players.SUMMARYTo sum it up, Armello is well driven adventure-strategy game with dice rolls and a bit of luck, that resembles the style of board games. With a plenty of cards player may react to changing course of the game and adjust the strategy perfectly. This title alsom offers much to the people outside the genre, so for a reasonable price you may get a huge amount of fun.I have been playing this game from 0.3.5 ""Pride's Fall"" patch and game made a huge progress since.Strongly recommended."
76561198091995427,Not Recommended,290340,34052612,Posted: 5 August,all,Egotistical Giraffe,"Over and over, I've tried to give Armello a chance with an open mind, but every time I do I just want to vomit out all my disappointment for what this game could have been, and what they've turned it into: a pay to win game with a $20 paywall.If you play this game by yourself, it's somewhat fun because all of the characters that you encounter are rather balanced relative to each other. However, if you step into multiplayer, not only is it nearly impossible to complete a full game without someone leaving and the AI taking over (by the way there is no way that I've seen where you can reconnect), but the matchmaing system is god awful and I have about a 20% success rate at even starting a match.Okay, so let's assume the servers are having a good day and you get a connection, and nobody leaves. Well, maybe now you can have some fun with other people, right? Well, not really. You see, the game has 8 DLC characters, several of which are significantly stronger than the base game characters. Most recently, I've played against a Twiss (DLC character) along with a Barnaby and a Thane while I was playing Sana (all 3 are base game characters). The Twiss got 4 spirit stones (one of the two major hurdles in achieving a particular victory) before the dawn of day 3. From that point, it was a 3v1 against the Twiss (everyone used everything possible to kill her while ignoring other players), yet the Twiss still managed to win. This is just one of several examples where I felt cheated out of a potential good experience and victory.Another issue I'm having is the crazy randomness. Pretty much everything is dictated by RNG, including the card draws, the questing, the perils (including palace entry, a crucial part of the game), and even the combat itself. As I often play Sana, many times I feel like I can't get a single spell that can deal even one damage, while players like the Twiss seem to get the one and only card that can win them the game (like a Hot Rot Wine on the last turn on the last night in order to cleanse the king having just entered the palace on the same turn). The feeling is so unsatisfying when you are about to win through hard grinding for the entire game, and someone else instantly wins because of just because the computer decided to let them win.So if you'd not like to deal with the low quality servers, overpowered DLC characters, and painful RNG, then your only real option is to play singleplayer. But the okay singleplayer wouldn't be enough to justify the game's $20 pricetag. Sorry."
,Not Recommended,290340,30928727,Posted: 3 April,all,Zer0,"As mentioned by many, the bugs ruin what is otherwise a great game.  They are unbelievble to be frank (game breaking in many cases).  Good example, sometimes the game won't even shut down.  Or the main logic loop will freeze up and the gameplay halts entirly.  For the technically inclined, this is likely due to bad IPC or multi-threading.  That's an educated guess, I did not spend time dissembling,However, great art and game design with gameplay that's very unique and a breath of fresh air.  But not one of those companies willing to own up to their downfalls.  Instead releasing new content (which costs extra, fyi).  This is coding 101.  Bugs first, everything else second.  But that mantra does not appear to exist here.Is the game good?  Absolutely.  Is it stable?  No.  And that will kill your otherwise fun gaming mood in a heartbeat.  If there ever was an abandonment or the code open sourced (unlikely IMHO) then they could easily be fixed.  Until then I would stay away.  I'd create a community patch but I would likely be met with hostility, where other companies would welcome it.Hats off to the game designers and artists.  Credit goes where it's due."
