76561198160433325,Recommended,290340,28532739,"Posted: 22 December, 2016",all,StolenMadWolf,"When I first saw Armello, I thought that with the old Disney style animations it would be aimed for a younger audience, and I didn't put much thought to it. I thought it wasn't my kind of game. Then I eventully bit the bullet and bought it.And damn, this is actually a remarkably good game.Armello is a board game set in the Kingdom of... well, Armello. You play as one of several animal heroes who are all vying for the throne of the kingdom. The King has gone mad with a disease called the Rot and when he dies, the most prestigous hero will become the next monach... unless someone kills him first.It's quite clear as you look deeper in that despite the Disney style animation and the colorful graphics, this is a much, much darker game than it seems at first glance. The events that take place in the game, along with the dialogue and info on the cards tells a mucher darker story than what you would expect in the lore.You can select upto eight heroes, one from each of the four animal clans, being wolf, rat, rabbit and bear with the vanilla game, though one additional DLC grants you four new heroes and there are four more as part of a new Bandit Clan on the way. Each of these heroes has different stats and a unqiue perk to start off with and you can mix and match different rings and amulets to change up how that hero handles in game.The gameplay itself is easy to learn but is remarkably complex. Four players take turns moving around the board, taking settlements, completing quests, dealing with the King's Guard and Bane NPCs, the perils and of course, the other Heroes themselves. There is a day and night cycle which changes the conditions on the board and makes some Heroes stronger than others. As you play through the game, you can complete quests which allow you to level up your characters stats as you go along.You have a selection of cards to pull out of three decks, Item, Magic and Trickery, which lets you equip items or you can use them with their varying affects. Such as damaging another character or putting on one of the perils on the board.All combat and peril solving is done with dice rolls, any cards you have equipped or effects that have been applied to you can alter how much attack or defence you have guarenteed or how many dice you have amongst other things. Dice in the game aren't just RNG either, they are physically rolled much like real dice, although this can be a small pain for lower spec   PCs.This mix of dice and card based gameplay allows for varied tactics and approaches which often vary depending on who you play as. You can either enhance your character's strengths or remove the weaknesses to balance the character out. Each board is different each time and it offers varying oppitunities to play your game in different ways, and with four different ways to win, each game can be quite different.Now, the only con I've noticed is one you can't really eliminate with this kind of game with dice and cards. Luck is a big thing. There is a good chance someone is going to get all the good cards at the right time or get through without a scratch and go on to dominate the game. Others might not get anything good at all and fall behind the curve. Since there is no comeback mechanic other than getting lucky, this could leave one player just dominating and another player just left to wonder around the board unable to challenge someone or deciding to quit.Or those damn card players who get all the attack cards and keep killing you before you get close or slowing you down. It's really frustrating.Likewise, luck can quickly change the tide of the game quickly and as the game begins to draw to a close you can feel the tension as you try and play your approach and hope your luck holds. It's a little bit annoying but it's also what makes the game catch your attention and keep you invested.Regardless, tactics and strategy still apply, which can carry you through a game. The games can be quite long though, easily coming upto an hour or more, so keep that in mind.The game has quite a few things in it, singleplayer and multiplayer is both around, you have a card collection to see all the well drawn and animated cards you have come across in the game. All the games you complete will also give to a chance to get a chest or a key, combining the both together can give you dice you can use in the game itself.Both singleplayer and multiplayer offer numerous options to change up the standard gameplay, which is a nice touch.Now, some content you have to buy, though none of it's pay to win and it's not ridculously priced whilst adding additional heroes and new map styles, so it's worth the extra dosh.All in all, Armello was an unexpected little gem, it's a bit rough around the edges but whetever you are a furry or not, this game is certainly worth your while, with additional content on it's way. It's definitely worth your time."
,Not Recommended,290340,29267808,Posted: 15 January,all,Cinnamon Bear,"I really want to like Armello, but I have to say it has a few very large flaws, including one that has inspired me to write this review.Simply put, it is a lengthy multiplayer game. A game can take about 2 hours to complete. Should anything happen to a player's connection, there is zero ability to reconnect. Which means if you are playing the game with friends, you may find yourself having to start over after investing over an hour in a game, or you have to finish the game against AI.As a single player game, its fun but ultimately limited. And the lack of any ability to deal with disconnections/reconnections is a dealbreaker for multiplayer games. If I'm going to spend the time in a match, I want to know that I- and my friends- will be able to finish it.There are technical issues as well- notably I couldn't get the purchased DLC to actually work. The game can be fun, but I can't recommend it."
