76561198259237736,Not Recommended,290340,29649111,Posted: 2 February,all,penumbria,"I wish there was a ""I am neutral to this game""-button on Steam, or a rating-system using numbers or stars or whatsoever. Because all in all - while I would lie if I'd say ""Oh no, I NEVER had any fun in playing Armello!"" there are a few things that spoil the fun.Armello makes a wonderful first impression. It is a board-game with cards and dices, unique heroes which you can equip with different rings and amulets to suit your playstyle. The first trailer is nicely done (the soundtrack to that trailer is also wonderful), and the the following trailers (Horrors and Heroes / Ursupers) are quite enjoyable as well. The setting is also interesting - reminds me of the Redwall-series (with the benefit that the rat-clan seems to be the intelligence network, but not necessarily the evil guys), and that there are actually different ways to win the game sounds also quite cool. Most of the card-illustrations are quite well done, too - even having a flavor-text (though it took me a little until I found that out).  I can see and feel that indeed a lot of love went into the concept of the game.The tutorial consists of four little chapters; each of these is played with one of the ""classic"" four heroes (Thane, Mercurio, Amber and Sana), and teaches you what you need to know to play the game. A little tweak could be made here: you have the ""Burn""-symbol for challenges and battles before the tutorial tells you what card-burning is. And unless the game told you what it is you cannot burn cards. I was a bit confused at the beginning, so I would recommend to make the burn-symbol invisible until the tutorial reaches that stage.Sadly one of the most enjoyable parts in the tutorial is NOT in the ""normal"" Armello-game. As your hero wanders the lands, goes dungeoneering and questing (s)he can recruit followers. In the tutorial those little rascals say a few lines here and there, sometimes to explain things, sometimes just to create atmosphere. Which is really cool. Unfortunately - in normal games only ""The Stranger"" talks.I am not saying that my followers should babble endlessly. But for instance if The Bard gives you the prestige for escaping from a peril he (or she?) could say something. For players who find that annoying - including an option to shut the followers off should not be that difficult.Also the theory that you can win the game by 4 different approaches sounds better in theory than in reality. For the Rot-Victory you need more luck than for any other approach. Yes, of course you can equip the Rot-Amulet (once you unlocked it, which might end in a grind, even if you unlock it by battling the A.I.). But whenever I tried to go for a rot-victory I usually was not lucky enough to get my paws on cards which gave me rot (not even with Sargon, though it's a bit easier with him). So I am usually trying to commit suicide on a Bane a few times in a row, hoping that no other player (or no king's guard) is killing the Bane until I am done with it.Most players will go for Combat- or Prestige-Victory. If you find yourself carrying 4 Spirit Stones you could as well walk around on a mine-field, because everybody is trying to keep you from getting to the King by any means necessary. Yes, that is part of the game. If I got my 4 spirit stones basically by accident (because they spawned in a circle where I was standing, or I went through a circle with one, because I needed to quest, or I got it via a dungeon) I found myself having decent gear often, so I could defend myself. If I tried to gather them deliberately I neglected quests which would have given me gear/followers, because I wanted to gather my spirit stones faster... but then I seldom made it to the palace anymore, because every other player could beat me.Do not get me wrong - I KNOW combat is part of the game, and I behave COMPLETELY like that, when I see others having 4 spirit stones in their pockets, too. But that does not make the last 5-10 minutes of a game less frustrating.I do not know if it's possible to ""balance"" the 4 ways of winning the game a little better. After all, for every approach there might be a hero suited a little better to do this and that, but so far it feels a little... ""meh"" to know that basically combat- and prestige victory are the easiest way to play the game, when there are 2 other options as well.The next thing that keeps me from enjoying Armello throughoutly has something to do with League of Geeks themselves. Yes, I know they are a small company. Yes, I know the market out there is worse than a shark-tank. I have been there myself, and - though in another field - I am still freelancing. I am not hitting at the infamous ""laying their eggs into too many baskets""-topic (at that point I think they just overdid themselves, and people do that at times), but the way they are talking to the community reminds me of companies such as Riot or Blizzard. Yes, they are having somewhat of a ""dialogue"", but to me it does not sound like a dialogue, instead it reminds me of parents patting their kid's shoulder after the kid told them how much (s)he got bullied, saying ""There, there, it's gonna be alright, we'll think of something"" - and then they give the kid a sugar-cane instead of actual help.(Yes, that's really not the best example, but the best I could come up with right now).The Bandit-Clan is screwing the community. About a year ago it was said the clan would be released in Spring 2016. Then it got delayed and delayed, until we got told they would come with the iOS-version of the game. This version, however, would not be released around Christmas-time because of the huge competition on the market. Fine with me. But that was the last thing we heard. If you ask you get the same answer over and over: ""Hold tight for news."" Last time I heard that was last summer when I tweeted on a patch something like: ""I hope it [] comes to GoG, soon, too"". Well, I know how that turned out. I heard rumours about the Clan being released on spring 2017, but maybe that is just wishful thinking.The biggest annoying thing for me, though, is the server-instability. I get kicked from a game so often, and often enough when it's almost finished. Especially with the new amulett that you can only unlock once you reach player-level 10 it's one hell of a grind.So yeah, while I DO have some nice time with Armello, and I simply love playing games where I can feel all the love and effort that went into a game from the very scratch, I would recommend Armello only to people with a high tolerance to frustration (because it IS frustrating when you spend 40 minutes in a game and you achieved nothing, because the game just crashes).Still I have high hopes that the problems will get solved in the future, and I wish LoG still all the best."
,Recommended,290340,35060654,Posted: 19 September,all,Triton,"I have reviewed Armello once before in the past.  However, that was not long after getting Armello and before I put a great deal more time into the game.  I’ve played more than 50 hours of Armello now and I feel that my views would help people decide about this game.Most of the reviews I have read here on Steam for Armello are from players with less than 10 hours of play.  Considering the tutorial takes an hour or so and then the matching up of internet games does take a while, you are forced to wonder how many actual full games of Armello these people have played.  True, first impressions are often interesting to read but I am seeing many sweeping comments made by people who have not had time to learn the truth.  I hope to correct that here.Armello is a digital board game with very strong and balanced mechanics.  You will see people claim this is broken or that doesn’t work but the truth is they haven’t played long enough to really understand the mechanics.   Armello is easy to get started on but has so many layers to it that strategy can become very complex indeed.  There is only a minor progression system so long time players are not heavily advantaged over new ones except in one regard: experience.  By this I mean that these players have seen more of the cards, skill combinations and tactics than other players usually because they have been the victim of them at some point.  You cannot play 100 hours of Armello and be so “geared up” that you cannot be beaten.  However, if you learned a lot in that 100 hours, you can be a force to be reckoned with.People will often tell you that the DLC characters are “OP” or “pay to win”.  This is simply not true.  I have played most of my hours with the base game only and I win regularly.  The disadvantage of not having the DLC is that you learn about the other characters and their abilities through contact with people that do have the DLC.  There is no other way to practice.  Anyone who declares the DLC as “pay to win” but has less than 10-20 hours game time has probably never faced the same character often enough to work out a counter strategy.  This is a bad player not a bad game.Armello is visually stunning.  The characters, game board, dice and cards set the scene and tone of the game perfectly.  There is a feature that you cannot view cards that you have never drawn/seen in a game.  This means to be fully familiar with the game you must play.  No sitting down and theory crafting before you even start.  It also means that you can be totally caught off guard by something you have never seen before.  While most characters are geared for two of the possible victory options out of the four, you need to be highly adaptable and realise when you need to change strategies.  The claim that all games end in a Prestige Victory is usually a result of players not fully comprehending the time limit on the game.  You cannot sit around.  The game has a limited number of turns.  You must press your agenda.  Messing with other characters should never be at the cost of your own progress.I would highly recommend playing Armello to anyone who enjoys deep strategy games.  However, I also recommend you put some time into it.  You are not going to be truly skilled at the game with less than 20-30 hours of game play.  Don’t shy aware from facing experienced opponents either in multiplayer match ups.  When they beat you, they will be revealing their tricks and secrets to do it.  Snap up those morsels and trash the next guy with them.As mentioned before, you can still be competitive with just the base game and no DLC.  You will just have to carefully study the new characters and their abilities when you see them.  You won’t get to practice against them outside of multiplayer matches.I still rate Armello as one of the best digital board games I have ever played.  You will keep coming back to it and a game often takes less than 90 minutes to finish.  It can take up to four players but the AI is challenging enough that they won’t ruin a game."
,Recommended,290340,22997645,"Posted: 15 May, 2016",all,Yang738,"There is about two things that annoy me on negative reviews here. And that's complaining about the game being ""too random"" and ""long wait times"". Guys, seriously. Have you ever played a Board game? I don't think so.Also, unlike other Board games you actually CAN DO stuff while the other's are at turn. You can manipulate the enemy with your cards, you can set traps to avoid enemys approaching you or their goals. You can study their inventory and their goals.Rethink your strategy if someone is much further ahead of you with the same strategy.All these things you can do while the other's are at turn. And I think it gives this game a more strategic element that you think.Games are about luck as soon as there are dices or cards in it. Have you ever complained about Yathzee or any card game being a stupid boring game because you have to be lucky? Then it's just not for you.Overall I think this game is really fun, even with just a 25% win chance (because only 1 of 4 players will win)These negative reviews are mostly by people who are afraid of losing.I know this isn't a real review about this game but there are plenty of good reviews out there already so it won't matter."
76561197973212819,Recommended,290340,17889217,"Posted: 5 September, 2015",all,chronomodra,"Armello is a fun, addictive online board game for up to four players.  My friends and I have been playing it since it came out, pretty much non-stop.  And while we may scream in anguish after a particularly unlucky die roll, we always end up coming back for more.  An extremely tight and polished game.Pros:-Authentic Board Game Experience-Incredibly addictive-Beautiful Artistic Style-Four paths to victory, giving options for each player to always have *some* chance of pulling out a win, even if it's from someone else failing at the last moment-Multiple character types with unique traits and starting stats-Three card types (Items, spells, tricks) that work very differently to achieve the same goals, allowing for more diverse strategies-Dozens of unlockables with additional unique traits-Easy-to-set-up multiplayer, especially with friends-Relatively short but satisfying games (30-45 mins single player, 60-90 multiplayer)-Excellent tutorialCons:-A fair amount of luck involved, some of which can be significant enough to foil the most well-thought-out strategies-Can get heated in multiplayer, when someone chooses to attack/interfere with another player unprovoked-The random terrain might slant the game for/against certain people from the start-A lot of (often random) events can provoke excess frustration, such as getting a teleport/bane from a ruin, having wandering guards/banes move into your path, being hurt by the daily declaration, etc.-Getting across the map (usually to reach your quests) can feel painfully slow-One victory path (Rot) significantly more difficult and luck-based than the others-All followers and treasures (ie, the best gear) can only be attained through ruins and quest bonuses, and both of these are entirely luck based.  This can lead to gear disparity between players based on what are essentially coin flips.-No way to get back in after a multiplayer disconnect (though an AI will take over for you)-Some finicky, non-obvious rules are not covered by the tutorial, especially when it comes to gaining/losing influence and rot-Like most board games, will eventually get repetitive"
