,Recommended,290340,29451470,Posted: 23 January,all,AbaddonDrums,"To be honest, I have mixed feelings about this game. This is one of those games for which ""neutral"" opinion is perfect. So, what Armello is all about?It's a mixture of a board game, card game and strategy wrapped in gorgeous graphics and very nice soundtrack. Audio-visuals are very good and immersive. It feels like a fairy tale, every character is unique, likeable, and has a very cool design. Atmosphere is warm, nice, and calm... under one condition, and that is, if You have luck on Your side. Because this game can turn from a family friendly game to a table flipping rage fest. Why? Answer is simple, and to many people it's a turning point in buying a game or not. RNG! This game is so filled with randomness that sometimes You will feel You have no control over what's happening on the board.-Card picking at the beginning of each turn? Kinda random, except in one case if You have Usurpers DLC. One character can see what cards he's choosing.-Quests locations? Random. And the game is programmed that every time You complete one quest, next quest starts at the opposite side of the map/board.-Villages, main source of income for Your equipment? Random. So, it can happen that one person can have two villages nearby his clan grounds while another player has none and has to walk further to intercept it.-Exploring dungeons? Random. While exploring You can get many different outcomes, like finding gold/treasures, recruiting companions or The Stranger, spawning a wraith or even being teleported to another dungeon. The annoying part is that it isn't being determined by any factor at all, You just have to be lucky to get what You want.-And now the worst part. Battles with another players or npc's (knights and the king) are based on throwing dices, and although it's understandable it is random (since in real life throwing a dice is also random obviously) it presents a very, very nasty problem. The outcome of the fight isn't determined by Your playing skills but by sheer luck and the amount of dices You hold. The amount of dices depends on Your battle stat but even so there will be times when You're overpowered, having 7 or more dices and You still lose because RNG ""decided"" that You will roll 6 Rots and 1 Sword while Your opponents will roll 3 Wylds which gives them 3 additional rolls... and that can lead to another Wylds, and so on until You end up getting rekt. This can be very frustrating, to the point where You just quit the game. I would rather see some other mechanic that involves You as an active player more. You can burn Your cards to force symbols to appear, but that doesn't help much. At least not in my case.But despite all these flaws and rage inducing moments, I still enjoy this game for the most part. It may be because I am a calm person in general, but I can see how some other players will hate this type of gameplay. I wouldn't give this game a negative review, but positive one is also a little bit of a stretch, because that depends heavily on what kind of a player You are. If You are a rage quitter, You won't like this. But, if You're chill and aren't taking games that seriously, You can definitely enjoy Armello."
