76561198219988685,Recommended,290340,18376580,"Posted: 7 October, 2015",all,Authority Hound,"This is a beautiful game, graphically and mechanically. Armello mish-mashes several things I enjoy playing: card-based games, strategy, and tactics. This isn't just a ""beat your opponent to the King and layeth down the smack"", it's got far more depth than that. The methods of winning the game are part of the draw here: individual play styles can shine and are rewarded for the effort. Pacing your gameplay will depend on your play style.Artistically, the game draws me back to the worlds created by Richard Adams in Watership Down and The Plague Dogs, and the Redwall stories of Brian Jacques, all of which I enjoyed in my youth and still enjoy now. I actually like the disconnect from human-rendered characters as animals can offer similar, but much more mystical histories. As far as the story goes, there's not much more than a few simple bases: you're part of one of the four animal clans, you're attempting to dethrone the King, and each character has a special skill that can be used to essentially envision them within your own imagination. I like games that allow me to sort of ""flesh out"" a character for myself rather than having some contrived backstory forced on me, it makes each game more interesting and kind of intense as you're able to invent something for your character to be working toward upon taking the throne.Cons, I suppose, would be some of the things that I consider pros. Not everyone enjoys turn-based games, and waiting for the King's guard and the Bane to take their turns can become tedious (especially if there are a large number of them on the map), and not everyone enjoys card-based gameplay. However, if you don't like turn-based and card-based games, this one shouldn't even be on your radar. Luck is also part and parcel to this game, as it is with any dice-roll game, and if you don't like raw deals from Lady RNG, stay away; stay far, far away.One of the pros that I particularly enjoy is that each game can't just ""drag out""; the King has diminishing health and will eventually just keel over, ending the game whether anyone's breached the palace or not (no, you cannot heal the King other than one specific means). This keeps it from becoming stale, and since there's that added sort of time limit, it encourages progressive gameplay techniques that are learned from playing the game and understanding its tactics more.Another pro is the ""chat"" system in multiplayer games. There is no ""press-enter-to-type"" chat function, rather a series of basic dialogues available through the chat tab (like Hearthstone). I've long disliked chat systems in most competitive multiplayer because it seems like some people spend more time ""chatting"" (rather, trolling or raging) than they do actually playing the game. In the future, I hope that this minimalistic ""chat"" function is not replaced by a press-enter-to-type system; personally, I feel that it would hinder more than accentuate multiplayer. So far, the only basic way for someone to rage out and quit a match is to simply leave the game. I like this, I don't need someone's vitriol about being behind or ganged upon clogging up my screen. So, if a dev ever happens upon this review, please know that at least one fan of the game likes the ""chat"" system as it is; it keeps things far more civil in game.In all, Armello has an aesthetic that will either appeal or dissuade players in its art style, mechanics, and gameplay. It's easy to sink several hours into this game without noticing (or sometimes caring) that time has passed."
