,Recommended,290340,18128481,"Posted: 20 September, 2015",all,The Old Wolf,"Honor and courage. Trickery and deceit. Adventure and quests. Armello is a multiplayer strategy game that embraces several different styles of play and has a colorful cast of characters to choose from. With four different paths to victory, every game is challenging and requires you to pay close attention to your enemies each turn, and each game will be different. When I first read about the game, I thought it would be fun and interesting, but I didn't expect it to be so addictive! Reminds me a bit of Game of Thrones, but with anthropomorphised animals instead of Sean Bean. Whether you want to play versus the AI or with friends, Armello is worth the $20, and the community is friendly and helpful. I highly recommend this game to anyone who enjoys strategy board games. A+, 10/10."
76561198035742939,Recommended,290340,30069641,Posted: 20 February,all,Serx,"I had mixed feelings when starting Armello.  However I am a big board game fan. That tag got me interested in Armello.However I was rather concerned by the fact that it never was a real board game.  In the board game world that is the equivalent of a strait to DVD release.  They tend to be kind of poorly done.  I purchased this intending to use steam refund.However the game is one of the better games in the non-RPG adventuring genre.Like most games in that genre there is a ton of dice.  However Armello, unlike most, give a player a choice in what they want to do, instead of mandating go here fight this, etc.  It provides a variety of things to do and avoids a grind.But were Armello really shows its glory is the card play.  The game has great hand management.  There is definitely some tactics to when and how you play your cards. I even found myself debating if I should wait for optimal use or just play the card to get another draw.The game is competitive and does it correctly.  Most let you either just race or perhaps slow your opponents down.  In Armello you can actually hurt your opponents, but never remove them from the game.The theme for Armello is fine and I like the graphics.Now for the weakness --The game requires you keep track of the other players (at least to play on the top level). However what a player is doing is sometimes done so fast that if you blink you'd miss it.  Other times another players turn can be painfully long while you mostly sit there.  The game needs to speed its turns but also keep a log or make it easy to see what they did.In conclusion. This is a good game.  It is relaxing and crafted with a professionalism you do not normally see in this style of computer board game.  Solid graphic, solid game play with a solid recommendation.  Although sometime I wonder if my opinion is inflated due to low expectations."
