76561198026319986,Recommended,290340,18178915,"Posted: 24 September, 2015",all,firesorcr,"I really like it, as a big fan of Redwall and Miyazaki films and board games. It's really pretty with beautiful animations that ooze character, and easy to learn, and tough to master. There's a nice element of randomness that keeps it fair for people of all skill levels and makes it fun to come back and hope to see new things.So yes, I'd recommend it. That said, I have to complain about the fact that this is a ""board game"" where people can't have local co-op or hot-seat multiplayer; everyone has to have a separate computer and copy of the game to play, which is tough to organize and pay for. I would, for instance, really like to play this with my brother's family (my nephew would love Barnaby), but sixty more dollars for three more copies is prohibitive. I was also looking forward to playing this with college friends and their children, and can't, which saddens me. For a ""board game"" this makes very little sense to me.On a related note, please note that chat in multiplayer in this game is limited to a set of canned responses. I understand why this would be done (moderating chat is tricky) but it makes it near impossible to discuss strategy with other players, which can be unsatisfying when another player takes your ""Greetings"" as a threat rather than the intended friendly gesture and decides to hit you with an Immolation.Despite these absent features, it's still worth checking out, and I don't regret buying it, but those features would make it absolutely perfect."
76561198083702738,Recommended,290340,26193150,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,Slip N' Dip,"I absolutely love this game.  The only problem I have with it is that the multiplayer takes forever to complete one game.  This makes it really hard to grind for items which may or may not be intentional.  I would say if you were looking to play multiplayer, I would try to persuade some of your friends to buy it as well to make the game go a bit faster."
,Recommended,290340,28642410,"Posted: 25 December, 2016",all,[nBn] Kat,"Armello is an online multiplayer board game (although there's an offline single player option against AI, too) set in the Kingdom of, you guessed it, Armello, ruled by a mad lion king who's infected with Rot. It's your job--as one of eight (twelve with DLC) heroes from one of the four clans--to reclaim Armello by winning the throne, however you choose to do that. You can kill the king with pure strength or healing spirit stones, gain the most prestige in the land to usurp him when the time comes, or become even more corrupted than he is.The gameplay itself is based predominantly on dice and cards: cards grant you skills or bonuses on the field or in battle, while dice are rolled in battle itself to determine your attacks and defence. Of course, this means that luck--or the RNG--can disadvantage you, even in your starting hand, and the AI can utilize rings and tokens (which modify your character's stats during a game) that you have to unlock. In the couple of games that I've played thus far, I've felt a little as if the AI had more opportunity than I did, but I was still able to win.My only real complaint would be that, although beautiful (as is the rest of the game's graphics), the maps are fairly similar and feel a little small to me. I'm sure this is to keep the game moving and to force players into conflict, but it's a little annoying when you're trying to get to a certain square and all of your possible movements are blocked or risky to take. The game rules themselves are customizable, but not so much the maps.I would definitely recommend Armello if you enjoy a mix of strategy-based board games (with a hint of luck thrown in there thanks to dice rolling!). It's a beautiful game with a simple but clear story that wouldn't be out of place in Brian Jacques' Redwall series, and it's entertaining to play."
