,Not Recommended,290340,18345014,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,Zygon,"Pretty disappointing.I'm a big fan of board games, and was recommended this by a video reviewer I put good faith in.The game is gorgeous, and has a lot of charm, however the gameplay just doesn't hold up.Maybe it's because I listen to a lot of podcasts on game design, but this game was a fail. There's way too much luck involved, and most strategy you can conjure up hardly matters. The first two games I played I just happened to win because I was doing quests and playing cards when I could.A good game boils down to making interesting decisions, but when playing this game there's very few to be had. Most of it doesn't even matter. Do I pick the quest that gives me a 30% chance to get a Spirit stone and a spirit that I won't use, or do I pick the quest that gives me a not useful companion that gives the health I'll probably need?Do I win by killing the king because I happened to get some rot cards and died to the birds? Or do I kill the king because I got lucky enough to get two spirit stones from the dungeons and it was super easy to get the rest? It's just horribly dull.Gameplay boils down to. ""Pick a character, use amulets/rings to give them small advantages."" This gives you the illusion that there's strategies to explore, but in actuality it ends up more like this:Go to quest. Hopefully get something good out of it, or don't 'risk' it. (But good luck having any sort of a chance if you don't.) Explore dungeons, get random stuff, or don't. Get into fights. Win/Lose them depending on what equipment you happened to get and how lucky you were on your rolls. Someone on the board gets enough Rot/Spirit Stones/OP equips to kill king. Very little you can do to stop them. They fight the king and usually win. Sometimes they'll die in the process and someone else who did nothing all game will win instead. Game's over.I hope more people explore the interesting design space there is in a digital board game in the future, but this game felt like all style and not substance.If you're looking for a super casual game and have a high tolerance for swingy gameplay to play with a few buddies, then this is the game for you.If you want something anything deeper than that, look elsewhere.2.5/5"
76561198158149244,Not Recommended,290340,17848092,"Posted: 2 September, 2015",all,tuckboat,"UPDATE:11/18 -  My feeling and opinion on the game itself have not really changed from what I wrote before. I still find the game to be underwhelming and the enjoyment of it disproportionate to the love I see it getting. However, the community on the whole here has been EXCELLENT. I mean I have been pretty adamant (though respectful) in stating my opinions and I have to say with one or two excepetions the reaction has been civil. That does not happen on the internet. Except for here apparently. So if you are okay with taking the community health into consideration I am actually gonna go ahead and say I would Recommend this and move up my rating to a...5.1/10I also have to take into consideration that my expectations for the tile may have been too high. More frustarting is that many other people that like simliar games seem to be completely satisfied with the experience and delivery. Its pretty unusual that I wind up an outlier in satisfaction when I am (or felt like I was) a part of the core demographic. Armello seems to be enjoyed by people like me. I barely enjoyed it for 5-6 hours before I found myself searching for reason to like it but I just can't quite figure it out. Anyway if your on the fence I say give it a shot.11/9 Was pleased to see that with the new update the speed of the AI controlled players was adjustable. I would have to say that experience for singlplayer has been streamlined and improved dramatically. Sadly, I still did not enjoy the game. I only realized this after playing for another few games and realized I was searching for reasons to switch this game to a recommend.In response to Kletian's comments to my review:I agree that picking your deck can influence the outcome however there are just too many random variables that are outside of your control. Is this game strategically superior to chutes and ladders? Absolutely. Risk? Not even close. Monopoly? Probably the best comparison. The random or uncontrolled variables in this game include:3 other players turns1 King turn (King's Guards)Banes TurnPlacement of Quest MarkesCard Draw (Mitigated by choice of card type but still random)Dice RollsBoard ConfigurationThat's alot of randomness to contend with. I am in no way opposed to RNG or believe that it should be a left out of any serious strategy game. However the way this game is structured leaves little room for interesting choices as the game evolves. The randomn elements seem to dictate the way you should be steering your strategy and trying to go in another direction is almost always going to put you in the losers bracket. Armello offers you choices in your strategy but the design of the game itself hamstrings you into playing one way or the other and its just a tough pill for me to swallow.The game is still gorgeous and I agree with Kletian's comments that game is more similiar to Rouge-likes in progression type. However, I would argue that old-school rouge-likes rewarded you for measuring chances and taking risks which is something I found lacking in my time with Armello. The end result was that were often (not always) rewarded for taking those risks to gain advantages and overcome challenges. In Armello you are rewarded for understanding which path to victory is most likely to be successful and than gearing your startegy towards acheiving that goal. Abberations to this formula do exists but they seem far to infrequent and unintentional to be considered a part of the strategy.For a game that involves startegy and measuring risk I would recommend Chaos Reborn.I would take a pass on Armello unless you really love the art and animation (both are excellent).5/10OG REVIEW:I have very mixed feelings for this game. I'll keep this review short and update it as I play for longer.Current Playtime: 6-8 hours (5 games total on a friends account during early access)Pros- Original and creative concept for a game- Ran Smooth on low spec computer with med graphics setting- No bugs encountered- Beautifully Crafted World (card art and animation are my personal highlights)- Limited Game Modes at Launch (ranked coming soon per forum post)AC/DC-RNG Heavy from a double down effect of having card draws and dice rolls as random factors-Universal Card Selection (no deckbuilding element if you are expecting a more typical CCG experience)Cons-Repetition of Game Board Means it all looks the same after awhile-Some progression exists but a overall a little light on the RPG element promised-Balance - Several ways to win a game but two of these are extremely difficult to achieve-Long playtime for each game especially Multiplayer-RNG + Balancing Issues + Long Playtimes = Frustrating ExperienceEven shorter review:3-5 hours: Sweet! An Online Digital Board Game with RPG progression.5-8 hours: Slooow Moving Game (3 turns other than yours to contend with) and disappointed to find that a strategic approach is smaller element is secondary to dice rolls/card draws.I will keep playing as I still love the premise and several of the issues I have with this title have been acknowledged and are being worked on by the developers. Priced out at $20 US dollars in its current state I am going to have to give it a thumbs down for the time being."
