76561197983672075,Recommended,290340,19348320,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,DaetherX,"If you love those interesting tabletop board games, then you'll enjoy this game.Armellois an original digital media IP that has everything you'd expect from physical board games!Bottom line:Do I enjoy this game? Do I think its mechanics work well?Yes.I've played all 4 of the prologue (tutorial) chapters, and also played 4 regular games. I enjoyed playing, and each game was a bit different since the map is semi randomized, each character has different strengths, there's various quests to choose from when you start or complete a quest, and there's several different win conditions.The art in the game for the cards is very cool. Each of the cards has some little bit of animation like blinking/shifting eyes, or a forest whooshing by as a person runs through it, or a bit smoke moving. The art style of this game is wonderfull, but you can see that in the screenshots.The rules/mechanics:It has its own 6 sided die with symbols instead of numbers.It has 8 different characters, each with a unique special passive ability and slightly different stats. This means each character will play a bit different as one might be better at battle, but another might be able to cast more spellcards or more expensive spells.Each character has 4 main stats:Fight- Determines # of die you roll during battle.Body- Essentially is your max HPWits- Determines # of die you roll during Perils, a negative event card played on a space you entered. It also determines your maximum card hand size. You draw to this amount each turn.Spirit- Essentially your max MP, you restore to this number each nightAll 4 of these are also used in quest challenges where 1 stat point x10 = % chance to succeed.You also gain/lose Gold used in equipping Item cards / hiring (equipping) follower cards or playing Trickery cardsThere's Prestige that you gain/lose through certain actions like completing a quest, and some few Trickery cards will cost Prestige instead of Gold. There's a thing that is basically your current MP for the day. Finally there's Rot. If you are infected by this, you lose 1 HP per day and there's other mechanics surrounding this. The king is infected by this setting the turn limit for the game.There's a card system as mentioned as well. There's Items (including equip-ables, one use, and followers), Spells which can be buffs / debuffs/ or even direct damage to other characters, and Trickery (You triggered my trap card, Yugi! Sorry I'm unoriginal). Trickery cards most of the time are played as traps that can be set on certain tiles and when anyone enters that marked space they must pass a challenge by rolling the # of die equal to their Wits.There's a bit more to the game but that's basically it.The king is dying and mad (crazy/evil) due to Rot infection. You must have the highest Prestige when he dies to win, or you can kill him yourself and become King/Queen, or you can gather 4 sacred stones and attempt to cure the king and the land of Rot."
