76561198203401576,Recommended,290340,22294150,"Posted: 7 April, 2016",all,silverwolfdemon,"Armello is a beautiful but relatively simple board game.Armello excels in aesthetics and music but for some gamers (even tabletop gamers) the gameplay can be a bit lacking. How and if you win the game are heavily dependent on RNG. This can be very frustrating to players who want a more strategy based game.RNG determines the outcome of dice rolls, dice rolls determine the outcome of battles, battles determine the outcome of the overall game. To be fair, dice rolls can be manipulated by cards in your hand and by your equipped cards. However, what cards you get is up to RNG and you may end up with poor equipped items or a lack of the card type you desire for any particular battle. Also, the amount of cards you can hold is determined by your wit stat, which always seems to be lacking unless you are a rat (at which point you have very little of any other stat).Aside from RNG, my one qualm with this game is the speed. Waiting for turns to go through can be excruciating. While I recommend watching the characters (as you may find ways to trump them), there are times when all the characters are in stealth... So you will sit there, listening to them rummage around for a bit, waiting for your turn while almost nothing happens visually. I HIGHLY recommend turning on 'Quick AI Encounters' after your first game. This will speed up the turns quite a bit.There are 4 victories you are capable of attaining: prestige, kingslayer, spirit stone, and rot. By far, the easiest victory to attain is the prestige victory; it depends more on strategy than any other victory. Rot is the hardest victory to attain; it is highly reliant on RNG. If you are a completionist, or even just want to attain all the victory achievements, you will be kept busy for quite a while. However, if you are fine playing it once through, it will maybe keep you occupied an hour or two.I recommend the game if you like to fight against the odds and have decent luck with RNG.I do not recommend the game if you hate RNG dependent mechanics (for which there are many)."
76561198156626658,Recommended,290340,29761030,Posted: 7 February,all,Mad-Doggo,i love it. i feel like 80% luck 20% skill lol
76561198038424499,Recommended,290340,30068679,Posted: 20 February,all,Krishirish,"A great little role playing strategy game with cute graphics, excellent mood music and lots of replayability including online multiplayer.Armello is a well designed game whose main game mechanic revolves around traversing a fixed map of varying terrain and obstacles with your player character.  It is a turn based game which allows you build deceptively complex strategy with a little bit of luck.  Any person familiar with table top role playing will understand the mechanics of Armello well.  Gain cards in your hand and play them with the appropriate resources (money, magic and in some circumstances prestige or even health).  Move through the map gaining resources and doing quests (by landing on the quest tile and passing a short game of chance).The story behind the game is simple.  Armello's ruler, the king, is dying of rot, an evil infestation making him go mad.  4 seperate factions are vying to take control (wolf, bear, rat and rabbit) through their agents.  The base game comes with 2 agents for each faction.  They are well balanced and will require unique game play strategy to win.  The gameplay is relatively short when you get the hang of it.  Online mutiplayer is not a mode I have tried therefore I can't comment on this aspect of the game.That said I very much like this game.  It isn't an expensive game but the developers have contunually been adding elements and tinkiering with game play.  There are expansions which add 1 new agent for each faction and a soundtrack, but these aren't neccessary to have many hours of fun playing the game."
