,Recommended,290340,30150792,Posted: 24 February,all,Superscooter,"A board game with beautiful art, music and characters. Much like any game with dice, it heavily relies on RNG. The end result feels very similar to games just like 100% Orange Juice. Let me make this clear: this game may present itself as a strategy game based on how it looks, but it truly is a board game at heart. The only difference is you can play it online with friends. The store page DOES say stuff like ""deep and emergent strategy"" to describe Armello, and that is only PARTIALLY true. No matter what, there will be some actions you can think about taking that will probably benefit you in the long run, such as *attempting* to kill your character to make it to your quest faster, but you always have to consider RNG instead making you blow through what you're trying to die against. You can easily have a game where you reign supreme with good card draws and luck (Hot Rot Wine is extremely overpowered in any victory scenario, the steal others cards power should be cheaper and more common), and some games you accomplish nothing because someone else already screwed you over very early on (also making them highly unlikely to win if they also die) or the game RNG just hates you very much.The point here I'm trying to make is that you get a varied, different game in each session. Some will be really ballsy and take on the King early (watch out for the Sana), and some trip into a rot victory, although it is unlikely. Sometimes a player can get 3 Spirit stones in a span of fifteen minutes because no one interrupts them, they get a lucky stone circle spawn, and the stone circle luckily has the random quest that allows you to get yet another spirit stone. There is no competitive in this game, and there never will or should be because of how the game works, so I'm also baffled at how people complain this hard about how the game works. This isn't like XCOM where the entire rest of your game is screwed because the game decided it should be, Armello isn't continuous. It's an about-hour session that is separate from every other.In my last statement, I'm going to specifically call out the people leaving negative reviews just because now there are seven dollar skins that neither look impressive or cool enough to purchase. Who gives a♥♥♥♥♥♥ There's no doubt in my mind that someone is stupid enough to buy them, and regardless, they do not impact gameplay in the slightest. Same with the dice skins - you know, unlike CERTAIN OTHER GAMES with the chest/key system, in Armello you get a chance for a key and chest every single multiplayer game, win or lose. I would say this is very fair.TL;DR Please don't purchase Armello imagining it's probably some unique take on Civilization or grand/strategy. Instead, purchase it because of the fun you can have from the unexpected, even better with friends.P.S.: Please integrate the Steam feature ""recent players"" into Armello so you can probably make friends off of this game.Edit: When the hell will the mobile version come out"
