76561198132649389,Recommended,290340,21052501,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,BeardedFancyman,"EDIT:Forget what I said below... Im editing this review because I still come back to play this game, I still love this game, and Its still just as enjoyable as it was.I dont know what all the DLC related negative reviews are about... you dont have to buy any of it to play, but considering this developer is still updating after all of this time (and dont pretend you dont know the lifecycle of games on here or how quickly theyre abandoned), paying $6 for a cosmetic skin seems like not only a fun visual treat, but a nice way to keep the updates coming.This is still a really good game.___________________________________________________________________________I Love It!Dont be dissuaded by the (few) negative reviews, this game is very much a dice and card based tabletop boardgame, and it does that quite well. There are multiple ways to win, and certain animals have a slight advantage depending on the way you plan to win, not that you are AT ALL limited in choices due to the creature you chose as your avatar.Dying is a part of the game. You WILL DIE. But depending on the strategy youre using to win, you may find that an occasional death is helpful. There is a lot of strategy involved, and as other people have mentioned, one roll of the dice may see you needing to completely revamp your strategy... but as a tabletop gamer, I'm used to that, and find it to be part of the challenge.Single and multiplayer modes available, and I find the AI on single player to be challenging and enjoyable... you can invite friends to multiplayer games or just queue up for a pick-up.I got it for 25% off ($14.99), but it is definitely worth the $19.99 full price.As I write this, I have 18.0 hrs of play time, and that is in two days... so yeah, I kind of like it.If Settlers of Catan, Risk and Hayao Miyazaki had a baby, this would be it; and it is adorable!"
76561198051886049,Recommended,290340,16049809,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,Shiroe,"Aloha Steam-ers and Stream-ers,Warning: The following will be presented first by a short blurb about my thoughts on the game, followed by a very dense reflection on the aspects of the game and all the nuances I have come to find during this Early Access Period. If you just want the short and sweet Review, Look only to the first paragraph. If you want the Essay...continue ^_^--Blurb--Currently Early Access: Not all features unlocked, not everything is in final game form, soul of the game and it's potential is immediately apparent. Play with a friend or by yourself.Game of Thrones meets Redwall for an epic ride through the lands of Armello in the format of Settlers of Catan...without all the tradingThis turn based strategy desktop gaming with a furry overtone will have you forming secret coalitions, laying deadly traps, braving forgotten dungeons, hunting deadly creatures, and praying to the RNG gods for their blessing. With multiple methods to achieve victory and only having 16 turns for you to accomplish one of those conditions, this mad dash for the crown will leave everyone scrambling till the last second.Goal of the game: Become King....sounds easy right?How to reach that goal:Kill the King and take the throne by forceBanish the King with magic of the WyldWin the loyalty and support of the peopleEmbrace the Rot and become the new Dark LordPros (imo)-Achievement System: Good long term investment if you wish to discover different strategies of play-Card and Dice combat: Good Planning is countered by Good Luck and vice-versa, makes sure everyone has a chance-Questing System: RPG style of character building along multiple routes to aid you in your victory path-PVP and PVE Adventuring: Fight other players or monsters to enhance your chances of winning-Graphics: Beautiful art with minimal animations subtly draws you into the game as you play-Not a ""Winner's Game"": you've played them before. Everyone who spends 15 turns to attempt to achieve victory has a chance to achieve victory. Lovely aspect of the luck based combat system.Cons (imo)-Combat Log: When first learning the game, you'll be swamped by a feeling of ""what just happened"" a lot. The combat log is small and hard to keep track of since every turn is packed with so much information.-Early Acces Bugs: Not completed yet, so if you're looking for a finished and polished game, you will not be getting that right off the bat. Community and Developers are working to iron them out and plan on improving the game throughout it's life span-Hidden Information: Lots of things about this game I don't know about. I don't know what the goal is, payment plans, development schedules, etc. Putting a lot of trust into the developers. However, considering how much they've done with the game already, I don't think that trust is misplaced.-Addicting: This is just me.....I put it as a con cause you may have a life....I love being addicted to this game.Overall Impression: Love the game, can't wait to see what else they do with it. More characters, cards, etc. So much more is planned for this game and I am enjoying seeing what comes down the pipe.--End of Blurb-- (Yeah...THAT was the short stuff ^_^)--Beginning of Rant and Praise--The once beautiful land of Armello was ruled by a wise and benevolent King. The inherent animosity of the Bear, Rabbit, Rat, and Wolf clans were tamed under his rule. With fair hand and heart, the King provided a place where all would be welcome and war would cease. All was well and right in the world...until the Rot came. Dark magic permeated the land, spawning terrible creatures that roamed the night, preying on the innocent and frightened. With the King's guard called away to confront this evil, another evil arose to line their pockets with gold and wet their blades with blood. Without their protection, the citizens were terrorized by criminals and bandits who thrived in the chaos abound. The once peaceful coalition between the clans have been torn asunder and fear for the future has called the clans to call out for heroes, namely YOU, to claim the throne of a Mad King.The writing in this game, when I take the time to look at it, is simple and straight forward. There is enough spirit and wit (there is a pun there) in this game to give it a kind of life that seems like the next generation of ""board game"" feeling. Growing up with a large family, we had lots of chances to play board games with each other and the once powerful alliance of one game quickly became a bitter rivalry the next. With the dawn of video gaming (that should indicate how old I am that I witnessed this transition), that tabletop game feeling seems to have died out. Why bother playing with such a static field when the bells and whistles of computers and consoles are so much more appealing. Somehow, this game has found a balance between those two aspects. With the graphics of a console game with the core mechanics of a tabletop board game. What's improved is that nobody is saying ""that's against the rules"" and digressing into a 30 minute discussion about what the manual means. The rules are programmed in, and everyone is always subjugated to the same ruling. Maybe that will change in the future when they allow us to create our own games with ""house rules"", but it doesn't change the fact that the rules are always going to be implemented fairly.That's another big part of this game. Fairness. Although there are some things that need balancing still, the goal is to legitimately allow every player a chance at victory. Emphasis on ""Chance"". The luck system in the game keeps it so that there isn't really a ""sure way"" to win every time, you need to learn and adapt to the cards being played, how the board is laid out, and what your opponents are doing. Despite this, a ""good player"" who has strategy and executes their goals effectively will have a distinct advantage over a player who relies completely on luck. So there is a way to be a ""good player"" in a game and reduce the chances of someone sneaking a victory over you by being ""just lucky"".That being said, there are a few aspects of the game that could use improvement. Many of them are mentioned and developed by the discussion boards and forums. The developers seem to be actively interested in the concerns of their gaming community and address each presented problem in some way. Again, the game is still in early access, so there is much to be done, but I have yet to feel like this is a game that is already set in stone, and I am going to just play it. From the time I heard about the game to the time I started playing it, which was only a few weeks, the YouTube videos are already showing that what was mentioned has been addressed and fixed thanks to the watchful eyes of the gamers. It's a very rewarding experience to be a part of.One of the sad things is being forever in Queue to find a public game. Hopefully that will change when more people find out about the game and it begins to hit a larger audience. Playing with the AI, though easy to get a victory out of, allows you to polish and attempt strategies to see how the random luck player would do against you, but I am dying to test out my strategies on other players and interacting with them in this environment. The chat features are somewhat limited, but considering just how cut-throat this game is, perhaps it is best that players are not allowed to rage at each other with harsh words and foul language. This game really is ""you vs the world"", and though sometimes it may seem like every other character is just bashing you, you can still win. If 3 players decide to pick on only one person, and trolls will be trolls, there is still the chance that one person can sneak into the castle and Kill the King. Hopefully, if they change the Rot Victory prerequisites, if one person is being bullied in game, they can get ROT and win!..(am out of space)"
76561198001049127,Not Recommended,290340,23191366,"Posted: 24 May, 2016",all,Squaddle,"Having reached over 100 hours in-game, and with a new update recently released, I've updated what I had originally written to reflect both the current state of the game and my thoughts on the matter.TL;DR  -   Armello has a wonderful visual aesthetic and lore but has about as much ""deep and emergent strategy"" as yahtzee or mario party.  Gameplay has an overwhelming reliance on RNG, resulting in skill and tactics offering no significant impact on the game's outcome and making the gameplay generally frustrating.  Armello is additionally hampered by numerous graphical and UI bugs, a finicky matchmaking system, and one of the worst online multiplayer netcodes I've ever seen.  Well over half of the multiplayer matches I've attempted have never been finished or even started due to one of the issues listed above.Avoid if you have any love for strategy board games and videogames, Armello is nothing of the sort.----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------I originally wrote a review for the game last year, shortly after the game's release, with around four or five hours of gameplay on my belt.  Although the game had beautiful visuals and a stellar artistic design, I was more than a little bit disappointed in the actual gameplay;  over-reliance on RNG for most of the game's challenges left little control to the player and made most actions unnecessarily frustrating.  I could look past the frequent crashing, bugs, and the sheer difficulty of finding a full game, but the gameplay was a real dealbreaker.As of May 2016, the game's currently on version 1.3, and I have spent roughly 100 hours in-game.  There have been a number of changes made to the game's balance, additional content added, and some new mechanics implemented.  However, the real fundamental issues with the game were not fixed...  If anything, they've been increased with each update.  In it's current state the gameplay is so unbelievably FRUSTRATING that it overpowers whatever good the art, sound, and design give, and the developers really don't give any indication that it's ever going to change.  The real kicker here, though, is that most of the time you aren't even going to experience ANY of this.  The game's multiplayer functionality is completely broken and sporiatically functional, frequently crashing, freezing, or ending multiplayer matchmaking at a moment's notice.  The issues plaguing multiplayer matchmaking have been around since launch, but despite reassurances by the devs that they're working on fixes very little has actually been addressed.Let me explain my gripes with the gameplay in more detail.  Although the store page proudly claims that Armello has 'deep, tactical card play, rich tabletop strategy, and rpg element', spend a few hours in game and you'll quickly find that this is false advertising;  The gameplay is almost entirely dictated by randomness (in the form of card draw, success chance, or dice rolling), leaving virtually no room for any actual strategic planning.  When just going for a ride and messing around, the game's fine fun.  But, the moment you TRY to do something, be it as simple as moving to a specific tile or killing a near-dead creature, you'll more often than not be met with stupid amounts of frustration.Wanted to move a couple of tiles to reach a quest?  Oh, sorry, you spawned an enemy bane that knocks you back, wasting a precious action and forcing you into a combat.  Have six dice for a peril challenge and need to meet only one symbol to beat it?  Sorry, you never rolled what you needed and you succumb to the trap.  Need some defensive equipment to ward off hyperaggressive players?  Wouldn't it be fun if all you drew for three turns straight were scouting, rot-related, or sword cards?    Forced into combat with an enemy, and have to push it out of the way to progress?  Hah, wouldn't it be a shame ifyou dont roll a single goddamn shield, resulting in your spontaneous death and sending you back to start?This level of crap doesnt happen to you EVERY game, but its not a rare occurance by a longshot, and in each game hands down at least one or two players are going to get the short end of the stick while the others move unhindered.  A little RNG is good for games, as it keeps them fresh, but EVERY ACTION you can do in this game is a gamble with very little reward and a whole lot of risk.  And, unlike other games heavily reliant on RNG, there's NO limitations imposed on it.  You're equally likely to get ♥♥♥♥ed over when you're down as you are when you've spent the game trying your best to stay in the top.  When the latter happens, it's pretty annoying, but when the former happens you flat out want to uninstall the game.Even when I win, it never feels earned, and from personal experience none of the players ever leave these games feeling particularly happy or satisfied.  I WANT to like Armello.  I keep diving back in now and then and try to find some kind of enjoyment for this game, but every time I end up closing the game for the same reasons.  I do feel like Armello is a huge waste of potential and could be a much deeper, skill and strategy-based game... but right now its just 'pray to the RNG gods for good luck'.If you're art-focused and don't mind bad gameplay, can look past the astounding amount of ui, graphical, and gameplay bugs, matches randomly freezing, online randomly booting you out of parties, and horrible AI, you might enjoy the game more than I have.  But there's no way anyone in their right mind could ever call this mess a good strategy game."
