76561198006891555,Recommended,290340,15831930,"Posted: 14 May, 2015",all,Mahasuchi,"I don't think there's much I can add that already has been said, but here goes...Yes, it's a digital boardgame. There's a heavy focus on cards for items, spells, allies and playing nasty tricks on your opponents. One thing that differs from most turn-based games is that you can play many of these cards on your opponents' turn, so vigilance and timing is important. Both the AI and human players will play cards(if they can afford them) to stop your turn earlier or delay you in any other way. Not all players will like this, but it's definitely part of the game's strategy and I think hard core strategy players will appreciate this(after all I am one; takes one to know one, right?).Yes, several of the elements of the games are randomized. You roll dice to avoid traps and during battles. Your success in quests depends on how high your tested attribute is. Some players will not like this. However, it's not completely randomized. During battles and when evading traps, you can ""burn"" cards to directly add successes to your rolls. In quests, you can choose between three quests that test different attributes and even if you fail a quest, you are guaranteed a small prestige award and your tested attribute is boosted by one.One of the best things about Armello is balance. The game doesn't guarantee any one action during a turn will be successful. This means it's hard to exploit certain strategies and the Armello tends to reward the player who varies his strategies, at least most of the time. It also rewards players who adapt to ever changing situations. Players who unsuccessfully try to reach the same objective again and again tend to get punished heavily. That way, even a player who seems overpowered can be hindered significantly to the point that he is denied victory. On the other hand, a player who has started as the underdog can get the upper hand quickly depending on the situation. Armello teaches the player when to practice prudence and when to take risks. It also encourages experimentation. Not a lot of strategy games do this.No, it's not Disney. Don't be fooled by the cute-looking animal characters. Each has a deep and meaningful background story and the world they live in is pretty dark by cartoon standards. You can read all about it on League of Geek's website(just google Armello). More on this can be found in the art on the beautifully rendered(and animated) cards. A few of them are comic in nature, but most display sinister forces, wondrous treasures, powerful spells and sometimes, a cruel world. The object of the game is to dethrone the king(by any means necessary more often than not) and every part of the game demonstrates that. The music is almost melancholic in nature, it reminds me of winter for some reason, but it fits the atmosphere of the game nicely and is very pleasant to listen to.Yes, the game is not finished. There are still a few problems with the public multiplayer systems, but the developers are working furiously on it. You can still enjoy a private game with friends or go head to head with the computer in single player. The AI is not the smartest, but it can still surprise you from time to time. Either way, it's constantly being improved. There's plenty to unlock and discover in the game while you wait for the full release. Every game is 30-45 minutes, rarely going above an hour and very replayable. It's the kind of game you can play in between bouts of another Steam title to change things up, prevent boredom or avoid carpal tunnel syndrome from excessive button-mashing.All in all, a great game, with the potential to be greater at its official release."
,Recommended,290340,17112890,"Posted: 18 July, 2015",all,The Underachiever,"Mercurio weighted the Spirit Stone, smiling to himself. This was the last one. He had everything he needed to break the curse that had nearly devoured his king. And it was just in time - the king's mind faded with each day, and before long he would be beyond saving.On his way to the castle, Amber, the infamous gold-digger crossed his path - the ignorant fool! Couldn't she see that his task was infinitely more important than quarreling over riches? Mercurio felt little regret as he pierced her heart.To make things worse, Thane, the lord steward, fell to the curse, too, and driven mad with the rot, he was battling his way through the king's guardsmen.Unfavorable circumstances forced his hand; Mercurio had quite the way with words, and a fat purse to emphasize his arguments. He claimed the title of lord steward just in time to sign a decree that rallied additional warriors into the castle.The king was safe - for the time being. All that remained was to overcome another valley, another forest; and the ever-present Banes.It was a rough journey, but Mercurio did not come so far to fail now; battered and bleeding, he stood before the palace gates at long last... imagine his surprise when the very guards he rallied to ensure the king's safety approached him, weapons at ready!While he was busy battling the Banes, Thane, the corrupted madman, had put a bounty on his head!This was the moment of truth. Mercurio played all his cards, pulled all the strings; accompanied by a group of mercenaries, he cut his way through the royal guard and into the throne room, hastily applying the Spirit Stones -despite the circumstances, HE DID SAVE THE KING AND ENSURE PEACE AND ORDER THROUGHOUT THE REALM!---The point: this game is absolutely charming and magical, and the people behind it clearly love what they're doing and care for Armello.Worth every penny <3"
