,Recommended,290340,21320618,"Posted: 19 February, 2016",all,Mysfyt,"This game is chocolate-covered bacon. A flashy video game with the heart of a solid board game. A sweet coating of eye candy with dark undertones. The gravity of Game of Thrones blended with the charm of Redwall.Given a casual glance, this may appear to be a strategy game or RPG, but make no mistake... this is truly a multiplayer board game experience in digital form. Expect much card-drawing and dice-rolling. All players take turns in succession. Complete games are fairly short, about an hour or less.It's very tightly designed, trading unnecesary complexity for satisfying depth. Each playable character has its own unique strength. While waiting for your turn, you are able to choose quests and play cards, so the thumb-twiddling common in many board games is minimized. Breaking from strict physical game tropes, there is a modest amount of progression in the form of unlockable amulets and rings that grant bonuses.On top of all this, it's very pretty, the character designs are delightful, and the animated artwork on the cards is just wonderful.It is not without its faults, though. Randomness plays a very large role, especially since conflicts are resolved with dice rolls. However, you can ""stack the deck"" in your favor with equipment and followers, and by burning cards. Also, the AI tends to make some pretty silly decisions at times, particularly when it comes to attacking the king. I have not played public games, so I cannot comment on the general experience there.Overall, Armello is easy to recommend if you love board games with dice and cards, especially if you can play with friends. If you are not a board game fan, this is still worth a look for its uniqueness and fun multiplayer."
,Recommended,290340,21356927,"Posted: 20 February, 2016",all,Sparrow,"Armello is an engaging game that I really liked. It has it's basis in board and dice games, and I found the learning curve pretty easy. The graphics and music are beautiful.It has single player as well as online multiplayer. Each game takes roughly half an hour. There are 4 different ways to win suiting different play styles, fight (fight and kill the king, and live), Spirit stone (Gather 4 spirit stones. You don't have to fight anyone if you don't want to), Prestigue (have the most renown from completing tasks/killing banes or other heroes when the king dies) and Rot (one of the hardest victories for me.)I would definately recommend this game."
