76561198313355806,Recommended,290340,31250140,Posted: 19 April,all,MockingWraith,"This is such a fun, and amazing game, and really a work of beautiful art, the gameplay is so addicting and is one of my favorite games ever!"
76561198052325510,Recommended,290340,25347019,"Posted: 4 September, 2016",all,Ragjan,"It's like a virtual board game!Armello is a strategic and turn-based board game which feels to me like a mix between Endless Legend, Heroes III and competetive boardgames -It also contains a pinch of Game of Thrones!.The game takes place in a fantasy universe inhabitated by animals with humanoid characteristics. Upon launching a game you'll be able to pick from an arry of different heroes - each one of them having special strenghts and traits depending on their ""animal clan"" (There are rats, wolves, bears and rabbits). The map is open to exploration and consists of tiles.You'll then spawn on the map and from there on you have only one goal - to defeat the other players and to kill/replace the dying and insane king. You can archieve this by different means, there are four ways to win the game - by killing the king in direct combat, by banishing him through the use of ""spirit stones"", by waiting for him to die while having the most prestigue/influence in the realm or by becoming more corrupted than the king - and slaying him in close combat. The entire game is round based and lasts up to 10 rounds (~19turns).Every player starts with a set of cards, some of them being useable skills and some being items. They can be equipped/used by investing spellpoints or coins, thus adding a tactical approach to the game. Items will influence the combat against other heroes and NPCs and you'll have to consider how you want to use them. There are also tiles with perils, dungeons, poison swamps and mountains, all of them having different effects on the characters.The combat system is heavily RNG-based but also contains tactical influences to some extend. Upon starting a fight each side will throw a certain amount of dices, the symbols will determin the effect (either defense, offense or nothing). The outcome of the fight will determin if damage was taken. You can burn cards to influence the outcome of a duel. If a hero dies he'll respawn on his starting field.Lastly I found the graphics of Armello and it's music to be beautifully made, and I really enjoyed the combat animations and the attention to detail which was put into the game! If you like competetive boardgames and (maybe) have some friends to play with you'll surely have lots of fun for a long term playing. Playing offline is fun as well, but certainly shorter lasting than the multiplayer!"
