76561198074378373,Recommended,290340,18117999,"Posted: 20 September, 2015",all,dm.harlin,"I bought Armello upon release, something I don't usually do (wait for patches/sales/etc), but I don't regret it.Basically, it feels like a great board game ported to videogame world.Pros:- Overall great game mechanics: balanced enough so skill/experience matters, random enough to make it interesting and not pre-defined- Dice-based combat- You have a lot of options and strategies to pursue during your turn- Good art (especially cards) and lore- Flawless Linux version (single player)Cons:- Problems in multiplayer (see below)- Minor flaws in the interfaceOK, not for the hard part. So multiplayer clearly has some issues, and while some of them (network problems and game-stalling bugs) can be expected to be fixed in the near future, others are more tricky.The average multiplayer game lasts 1 to 1.5 hours, and you don't have much to do during your opponents turns and game events (King's Guards and Banes) - that is, 70 to 80% of the time.It would be perfectly ok for a BOARD game, where you can chat with your friends/fool around/do some diplomacy, but it i NOT a board game (although feels a lot like one).You even don't have an in-game chat, only pre-defined emotes.Some options to overcome this:- play with friends and chat in Skype/whatever- read Twitter/what you prefer during other players' turns- have a beer in hand (always helps)That being said, I still enjoyed multiplayer to a certain point, and single player is completely OK (although can get boring after 10-15 hrs)."
