,Recommended,290340,21570519,"Posted: 1 March, 2016",all,Farrel,"I have trouble finding the words to do Armello justice. It is a wonderfully thought up board game, but developed to be played in a digital format, as a result it can do things that tabletop boardgames just can't. Players using stealth vanish from the board, there are neutral 'characters' who have their own agendas in game, the game itself is very carefully crafted and cleverly put together to be interesting and gets very challenging if you go online.But all of this is secondary to the one thing that League of Gamers utterly nailed, and that is the theme. The aesthetic of Armello is a joy to behold, from the serene looking map and hauntingly simple but evocative background tunes to the cheery character designs and battle animations and card art that will make you want to stop and take the time to appreciate it from time to time.Okay, sure, the AI players are a little easy and finding a game online can be a little difficult depending on your time zone and when you're looking, but there is still development going on and content being added, with the Bandit clan DLC on it's way and recent 'the stranger' update shaking up the ruleset a little, it seems hopeful that we'll see some more expansions and further improvements to an already wonderful game.Highly recommended to any lovers of board games."
76561198067970439,Recommended,290340,23101454,"Posted: 20 May, 2016",all,Stephanie,"I'm over 100 hours into Armello now, mostly in multi-player.  The game is a real hidden gem; it's fun, it's cheap to buy, and it's still getting cool new stuff added to it.I enjoy the competition and wild unpredictability of multi player mode the most, but be warned: it's a turn-based game, and sometimes you get a player or two that is reeeeeeally slooooow at taking their turns, which really ruins the game flow.I think as time goes on, you'll be seeing mostly players who are pretty quick at taking their turns though. It's the noobs who tend to agonize and overthink their turns, somehow not noticing that the biggest factor is simply your dice rolls.  And once the current sale is over, I think we'll be seeing a lot less noobs.For sheer fun, and cartoon animal silliness, Armello is a definite 10/10. And if slow turns get you down, there's always single player, which plays VERY fast. Almost too fast, because AI opponents love to try to kill the king and end the game ASAP. Make sure you're always #1 in Prestige ranking when you do single-player, cuz often the AI opponents aren't even close to being geared enough to kill the king and survive, so the winner ends up being the player with the highest Prestige."
,Recommended,290340,23146743,"Posted: 22 May, 2016",all,Gnaw,"Usually i'm skeptical of games that try to fuse too many genres, but Armello does it really well. The strategy, CCG, and RPG elements and each simple enough that the game is easy to learn, but they blend in organically so the game achieves and depth through width. Plus, the individual charactes have a good amount of balanced variety so you can either rely heavily on the game mechanics you like the most or do a bit of everything and still have a chance at winning. The game does rely heavily on RNG, but there are countless ways to control it and effectively doing so is what makes you a good player. Bonus points for having a great art style. Well worth 20 bucks."
,Recommended,290340,24032625,"Posted: 2 July, 2016",all,Zalbraxes,"This game is simply wonderful.It has a story, and a very good one at that. Its not even a story that you can act upon, since its, you know, a board game. It works as the setting to the world the game happens on, explains why youre doing what youre doing, and it even expands farther from whats needed to provide depth. There is even lore to explain what exactly is the Rot, which is a game changing mechanic, even though you dont really have to know what it is to appreciate and play the game.It has quests. No, it doesnt have level ups or anything, the quests are simply there to take you to your objective (and equip you on the way) to take the throne. If you pay attention to the questgiver's dialogue, it expands upon the aforementioned lore, so you know what your chosen hero is going through even though you arent in 1st or 3rd person controlling mode.Speaking of characters, those are charismatic, and each has its own lore and gameplay. While you can finish the game by completing any of the objectives, its clear that some characters are better suited to some victory approaches than others. This makes for a varied strategical touch, and adds a lot to the games replayability and, given that its a multiplayer game, its not as if you will only want to play this once anyways.Lastly, graphics and animations are amazing, music is impressively good (you dont mind at all that its being looped), and the spell effects are beautiful. As for bugs, so far I have encountered only one kind, which stops game flow when someone drops from the game; seems to be a bit random, although it may be caused solely when the player disconnects during a load screen. And for those of you worried about raging players, fret not, there isnt an open chat during matches; all players are limited to a quite big selection of interactions, roleplayed by the chosen characters.Overall, great game, fully recommended, way worth the full price, and it still has unreleased content, so keep an eye out for updates."
