,Recommended,290340,19799111,"Posted: 20 December, 2015",all,I'm Not Sue,"Having watched this game through Early Access iterations and release, I can say that the game is fun and also that the devs care that it is in a good state.HARDWAREGTX 970, Phenom II X6 @ 3.2ghz, 16gb RAM, SSDMouse and KeyboardSteam Controller -Works great, see below.Performance - The game never drops below 60FPS and looks great 98% of the time.  Minor texture flickering may occur and occasional audio performance issues from using the newly released Steam Controlled and Big Picture mode it seems.  The game is being constantly updated.  I have experienced NMA (no more action) bugs only twice or so in my 74 hours of gameplay, some other minor bugs after its release from early access as well but the release is solid and you should not experience any real issues either.  Netplay seems to work very reliably and has Steam integration for playing with friends.Gameplay - Armello is more or less a tabletop board game where you control one of several semi-customizable heroes in your quest to be the new king.  This is achieved by acruing the most prestige when the king dies of a magical corruption (or failed regicide), killing the king and surviving, or by collecting four artefacts required to cure him.   You have several decks of cards with themes of equipment, magic, and subterfuge, which you can draw and play towards your goal.  There's choices on how to progress your character, risks to weigh against rewards, and plenty of tussles to be had with the other players as you fight each other along the way.  The thematics in this game are all wonderful, and the art, music, and visuals all contribute to the great presentation.  The duration of a full-length online game is about 45-90 minutes depending on how long people take on their turns, and it can be less if a player achieves one of the other victory conditions,But is it fun?  I think so.  The game has a strong element of RNG.  Random board terrain, cards drawn, AI character movement, fickle dice rolls, and other players strangely unpredictable behavior all contribute towards making the game seem a crapshoot.  One of the more prevalent complaints I have seen is how RNG heavy the game can be.   But strategy does exist and a large part of it is being adaptive to the state of the game and trying to sway the odds in your favor.   Knowing what decks to draw out of to try get the right cards you need, knowing what your objective should be for that phase of the game, and knowing what victory condition you should be working towards (and not just wandering the board aimlessly), these are all important and more.  True, this isn't always going to work, but the game would probably be a lot more boring if every player was able to run consistent strategies, or only a few consistent strategies existed.  The randomness of the game gives you more unpredictable 'oh-my-god that just happened' moments.   It wont require any sort of grand strategy game knowledge to enjoy yourself either, so if you like to just play by the seat of your pants you can do that too.  I think most importantly, if you can be a bit laid pack and not get upset over the outcome of a dice roll going completely wrong and maybe even losing you the game every now and then, you will have a good time.All in all, its a great game.  I've played 75 hours and loved them all, and I hope to play many more.  There's been a lot of balance changes from Early Access up til now a few months after release and the devs do have an ear to the community for the most part.  There's some more content on the way in the form of new characters as well, and maybe even some more content DLC down the line (I hope!).  Its a good one.  I'd recommend it.-STEAM CONTROLLER-Game works great with the Steam Controller!  I would recommend my custom setup I have uploaded to the community profiles section, or you can read my suggested binding here.  This arrangement lets you easily and quickly view player positions and keep an eye on the action.  I put left click on the left side (unlike the default for steam controller) because it felt more intuitive to grab cards located on the left side of the screen that way.I'm Not Sue's Armello KB BindingsLEFT BUMPER assigned to Right ClickLEFT TRIGGER assigned to Left ClickRIGHT BUMPER assigned to Hero Shelf (H)RIGHT TRIGGER assigned to Inventory (I)STICK assigned to w,a,s,d respectively.RIGHT PAD is set as mouse.  Customize sensitivity to your preference.  No click action.LEFT PAD is set as Directional Pad. Assign buttons to Focus Player (1-4), keyboard 1, 2, 3, 4, and click action to Focus Quest (Q) Q.  Require Click is off.Assign mode switch for the LEFT PAD to LEFT GRIP.  Scroll clockwise and counterclockwise to Camera Zoom In and Camera Zoom Out (mousewheel up / mousewheel down).RIGHT GRIP is assigned to Focus Active Player (Spacebar)LEFT GRIP is unassigned.Y BUTTON is Roll Dice (R)A BUTTON is Left ClickB, X BUTTONS are unassigned.< BUTTON is Show Scoreboard (Tab)> BUTTON is Menu (Esc)"
