76561198059779238,Recommended,290340,14639557,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,vengeful5values,"**Edit since the new update**** Edit** I really love the new updates that they've given to the game -- the quests now lead you right up to the castle to defeat the king -- giving you at least a chance to be able to confront him or not. New cards have been added. And after a few playthroughs, the cards have become quite strategic in countering your rivals or enhancing yourself. A subtle thing that I love is the day descending into night and vice versa. As your turn begins, it is the very break of day and as each player takes their turn, it gets darker and darker until actual evening. I really like that. My love of the actual game is starting to lean towards actual fun and recommendation. :) If they keep enhancing it more, I can see Armello being something truly special. ** Edit **I don't think I can mask my disappointment with Armello. I seen the previews, I love anything with animals and love RPG's and card games. I guess, in my excitement for something new, that I glossed over the ""board game"" aspect of it. That's what Armello is -- a digital board game.The story is very intrigueing and I love it. I love anything new and different. But, with just a digital board game aspect, I don't see how the story can unfold -- the way it could with a card game or RPG. ...You start the game with the king already consumed by the rot. You and three others journey across the board. You have a few ways to win: gain prestige until the king dies, gain more rot than the king and battle him, confront him without the rot and battle him ...Questing takes the form of dungeons on the mountain hexes on the board -- it's random what you get: either coin and objects, or a clash with a dark specter. You can also quest across the board on various tiles, performing either acts of good deeds or not. You are given three choices to make and each choice will get you a different result. Perhaps this was the rpg aspect they were advertising. Or maybe it's the table top aspect that was completely lost on me.The card game aspect feels like an add on. Again, I guess I was expecting an actual collectable card game type of thing. ... But the cards, themselves, are beautiful and a new and interesting aspect about it as each one has something animated happening in it. I've played a few games and for what it is, it's a fun way to pass the time but ... I guess with this particular game, I was hoping for something more.I'm torn about this. I really want to love Armello ... but an hour and a half of a play through as opposed to taking my time and exploring or going on a side quest to do something else, the count down of the king's life is an ever present thing.Maybe when the game devolps beyond what it is right now, I may look at it differently. I *am* in love with the story and the animal world that they've created. It has amazing potential to go in so many different directions -- books, tv/movie -- maybe an actual, traditional rpg game in future, I don't know. But I will definitely keep watch on new and upcoming updates with this game and this world.In the end, it depends on what a player likes and wants. Some people are into the traditional table-top paper/pencil experience. I suppose, in this regard, Armello seeks to deliver. If it's something more like Final Fantasy or Magic the Gathering, it's not like that all.I recommend it for a new and different experience -- and for the story. It might be what other people are looking for and others might be wanting something different. It's difficult to really say where a recommendation is concerned. If you want to take the chance, put some money down to check it out."
