,Recommended,290340,22181213,"Posted: 1 April, 2016",all,Ryebread,"Armello is a beautifully picturesque board game. From the thrilling battle exchanges, to the delightfully animated cards and intro sequence, to its storytale-like writing that paints a small saga for your character through your quests, this game is a treat for the eyes and a fun dice-rolling way to occupy about an hour. However, as Armello is primarily a board game, you may turned off by its randomness and its slower pace.For me, Armello's chief strength is the quality of its visuals. You can see this yourself, as a number of a YouTube gaming channels have recorded their playthroughs of it during Early Access, including:Northernlion;Stumpt; andJesse Cox. There have been a number of changes to the game since it exited beta status, but what you can see from those channels is largely how Armello looks in its final state. You should also notice the ""talking woodland creatures with swords and magic"" theme, which can prove to be quite the nostalgic bonus for those of you read Redwall novels and Mouse Guard comics. Armello also features a ""dynamic sandbox"", which essentially means every game will have most of the terrain tiles on the board randomly generated, ensuring a different experience and requiring different tactics for every game.It must also be noted that Armello is quite friendly to new players. While the game starts off simply as your chosen avatar explores the land, a player can be swamped by the variety of cards and events he'll face. Fortunately, the game is very informative through its in-game guide (easily accessed from the main menu and during play) and is sufficiently detailed in its hover tips. This is especially the case with the cards, the major method you'll be using to interact with Armello's world. Each card comes with a short but clear description of their uses, so the player should never be left in doubt. Furthermore, the game has already seen two patches since its full release, and both patches have added new free content to the game including new items and cards. Details on these past updates can be foundhere at Armello's website. As is apparent, Armello has a dedicated development team behind it, one that fully intends to keep the game alive by bringing even more to it through future updates.Mind you, if you find yourself frustrated with the randomness and waiting of board-games, then Armello may similarly irritate you. While some strategy is possible, victory in Armello is greatly dependent on the luck of the draw and the luck of the roll (though this can also be an appealing spice for the adventurous). Also, every game of Armello requires 4 players, whether they be human or AI controlled. This means you'll find yourself sitting through quite a bit of downtime, watching other players go through their turns. In the game's options, you can opt to skip AI vs AI battles to lessen your waiting time, but you can't fast-forward all of it. You could leave the computer while AI turns play out, but watching other players' moves is also part of the game (i.e. planning your own moves based on where your opponents appear to be going or what they may be planning to do).All in all, Armello is a wonder for the eyes, and one round is a delightful way to spend half an hour to an hour. While PvP games online are completed in one go, offline player vs AI games can be saved and continued at a later date, making this game a fine option for a short spot of casual fun as well. If all this tickles your fancy for fantasy, delve deep into Armello and try for the Lion's throne."
