,Recommended,290340,20690709,"Posted: 22 January, 2016",all,[HoM] red_dorian,"The art style and presentation is excellent; this is very much a digital board game, and has the look and feel to match. The gameplay is simple to grasp: move around the play area completing quests and the like to reach one of 4 win conditions. Variety, depth, and replayability comes from the 8 characters; unlockable buffs; and a large number of cards to reveal.I played through the tutorial just to get an idea of how the game plays, and I was instantly hooked. I have only played through 1 full game but will definitely replay as it is very fun and compelling to play. I've two main gripes with Armello.The first is that there can be a lot of down-time between turns while the AI/other players decide what to do, which would be fine in a table top game, here it leads to boredom. You can speed up AI turns, but I imagine that when playing with 3 other people will lead to very long games.My second gripe is that there is not a lot of interraction between players. You can lay traps (You've activated my trap card!) and cast spells on them, but a lot of the time the only way to sabotage someone's plan is to out-and-out attack them (if you can get to them, movement is slow enough) or to pip them to the post and win faster than them/complete an objective faster than them.I would recommend this if you like board games, but maybe put on a show to watch when it's not your turn, or have voice chat to allow witty reparte and the lively back and forths that you get with IRL board games."
