,Recommended,290340,20921334,"Posted: 2 February, 2016",all,ＩＲＯＮＩＣ,"Armello is essentially a digital board game and a very good one at that. From turn one of this game, the player must make important, often risky, and game altering decisions that will shape the way they and other players progress to the end of the game. There are as many avenues for victory as there as there are players in a game which always leaves you with an opportunity for victory despite your circumstances. The small victories and defeats you experience will keep you engaged in the game up until the very end where the game's stakes rise as each player makes the final preparations for their win condition (though I concede that sometimes turns can take a little longer than I'd like). As with any multiplayer game, it is best played with friends as you will often find yourself deliberating and even deceiving them as you play. That said, I think this game would benefit from having a text chat to be able to better communicate with players in-game as the only option to do so right now is through pre-determined phrases (which have an element of humor in their own right I'll admit). The reason I bring this up is because the game claims to offer opportunity for alliance between players but in truth this can only be achieved from a few select cards and potentionally King's Declarations (this issue is, of course, circumvented through voice chat with friends but leaves solo players at a disadvantage). Ultimately, this game is a very fun and charming experience and anyone interested in this style of game will likely find themselves addicted."
