,Recommended,290340,26967197,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Die In Obscurity,"As a big fan of board games, I have never really enjoyed any video game version of a board game. Too many board games that make their transition to PC seem to stay too faithful to their source material, and don't realy take full advantage of what they can do with the medium.Armello is able to avoid this issue by being built from the ground up as a video game in the style of a tabletop board game. It utilizes mechanics like stealth which would be unfeasible as an actual board game, and wraps everything in beautiful visuals that really bring the game to life. Yet as a video game, Armello hits all the right notes as a board game."
,Recommended,290340,28501153,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,Worse,"I don't play a lot of board games, card games, or tabletop dice games, so considering that Armello is a mix of all three, that should frighten me. However, I do love the premise of fantistical, swashbuckling, swords-and-magic adventure, and when you add animal characters to the pot it happily brings me back to the days I read Brian Jacques' Redwall novels.A complete Armello game normally takes about 60-75 minutes, and there are four main ways to win: doing the most ""good"" before the turns are up is the easiest, while the other three can be much more challenging to accomplish. Over time it may be discouraging to see time-out endings happen the most, but I think a player needs plenty of experience, a plan from the get-go, and modest luck to reliably go for the quicker, decisive wins. I'm not there yet...The artwork is lovely and so are the landscapes. All of the design resonates charm and liveliness and presents a convincing world with a broad range of characters - but only on the surface. It was a little disappointing to see a lot of this detail come only through the art. There aren't deep backstories of the playable heroes, or lore that permeates throughout the world. Events don't really happen on a timeline or connect to each other very deeply. It's like there's either ""good people or bad people"", ""named character approaches you, you do one of two choices on a quest and that's the last you'll hear of him until you replay"". The players write most of the action while fighting, betraying and sabotaging each other, but that story always resets when the game ends and another starts. Basically, don't look for a compelling narrative to be there in stone.But this takes nothing away from the core mechanics, which are pretty balanced. Each hero specializes at doing something with the three card types, whether it's suiting up in the best equipment, weapons and armor, casting spells and boosting themselves (or crippling others) for a while, or setting up traps and causing havoc to tip the scales in a different direction. Managing gold and magic to do all these things is a tricky task. Anything drastic needs the right cards in your hand and every decision to spend or save them is nerve-wracking and exciting. They're good defense most of the time, but for me they're the reason I keep getting wiped off the face of the earth by lightning when I walk out of tree cover.I think the biggest issue I have with this game is how easy it is to attack and how hard it is to defend. In most circumstances there's 3 sides of the die that grant strikes but only 1 side that provides a shield, nullifying a single attack; kind of unhelpful if strikes just outnumber everything anyway. So there's a lot of times where two battlers will just pointlessly tear each other to shreds, die, and get sent back to their homes in frustration. The game's tips do point out that combat is costly, which I guess kind of contradicts the thought that things should be settled on the battlefield. However, this ends up justifying the use of cards to do some of the fighting and keep the dice on hold.Overall, I think I'll get my money's worth out of Armello. It's not an exaggeration that this game sways in the balance of luck all the way up to the final turn and keeps things interesting and unpredictable. Armello is a worthy starting point in a genre I'm no longer unfamiliar with."
