76561198007149867,Recommended,290340,29838847,Posted: 10 February,all,The_Admiral,"So you want to be a hero, huh? Armello gives you the opportunity, ‘cause one way of the other, the rotten King is gonna die. You get to decide if you have the sword in your hand or not when he drops.I had seen the advertising for Armello for a long time, but passed it by. The art style with the animal characters was initially off-putting to me. But Steam advertisers wouldn’t give up. They continually presented it as a game that I might like and sure enough, I do.Armello is a digital board game. You are a clan champion in the land of Armello and the king is going mad from “The Rot” and slowly dying. To save the realm, you need to take King ‘Scar’ down. Even if you ignore him, he’s going to eventually die, the only question is whether you win or not.The game is turn-based, which I prefer, and is a virtual dice rolling, animated card playing nail-biter where anyone can win.  Games last around 30 minutes for single player on “quick” mode, to an hour or so on Multiplayer mode. There are built in times in multiplayer in order to keep the game moving along.There are four different ways to win the game and that adds some welcome diversity.I found that I do like the art style, the cards are really nice with a light humor that I appreciate. You unlock new cards as you encounter them in game, so (so far) there are no additional cards to buy. That may change with additional DLC. You can purchase a seasons DLC for $5 which add spring, fall and winter to the board color mix. It’s a nice touch and I recommend it. Some may feel that it is a money grab and that the seasons should have been added for free or been part of the base game. To that charge I respond, this isn’t EA, LoG is a small Australian studio – don’t be a hater. Help them feed their kids.You can play single-player against the AI or multiplayer against three human opponents. The single player experience is solid, although the AI is not terribly clever. Once you know what you are doing victory is common. There are four different character choices at the start, but with the Usurpers DLC expansion the list of choices grows to 12.I have experienced problems with the multiplayer game. It is not terribly smooth or reliable. I’ve been dropped from starting games, if two people choose the same character to play, that can be problematic as well.There is a decent choice of pre-made multiplayer communication options depending upon the character you play, but no open chat feature. This means that there is no dealing with the trolls of the internet and the filth that spews from their lonely chat box. This is a refreshing feature that I would like to see in more multiplayer games.When you complete a multiplayer game, win or lose, you receive something. Presently it is either a chest or a key. Combine both to receive a different, stylized digital die that you can use in future games or sell on the Steam community market. I find it a nice motivator to keep coming back and play through to the finish, even if you feel that you are losing.While the board is slightly randomized for each game, the whole is so similar that you may not even notice. As a result, many may grow tired of a similar experience after a while and find the game somewhat repetitive. Multiplayer games are the counter to that, it’s just a shame that they do not function perfectly.As a whole I recommend this game. If you like board games this one is an easy pick up. The rules are not difficult and you can pick it up and play a quick game. You can play with your friends and Steam helps to facilitate that. If only LoGs can remove “The Rot” in the multiplayer, this would be a real gem."
