76561198254877633,Not Recommended,290340,29262361,Posted: 14 January,all,brave_roaster,"Edit: This game breaking glitch has now occured for me 3 times in a row tonight. It's no longer occasional for me, it's damn near every match.TL;DR Unfortunately, DO NOT BUY THIS GAME UNTIL THIS BUG IS FIXED. $20 wasted.It's a great online board game, however, there is one critical game-breaking glitch at this time: If a player leaves the game early, the AI that takes them over can at times fail to do or end their turn. This requires all players quit the current lobby and suffer a loss and a timer pentalty on their next matchmaking game. If it happens several games in a row the queue can be locked.Additionally, the mechanic when rolling in Perils should get reworked. The roll dice should be a button and not a drag and drop mechanic. Several times I've gone to burn a card, and have had to drag the card over 3-4 times. The timers are short so it's critical it needs to work the first time. Occassionally, when you do this, it will glitch and toss the dice instead. They need to make one or the other (Peril or cards burning) a click button and not a drag/drop mechanic. It doesn't work when they're both so close if you have like 7 cards to play.Aside from buggy Peril and AI mechanics, the game itself is fun and worth the $20. If the AI glitch happens to you, hit escape and in the top right click the bug icon. You can submit a bug report there. Maybe it will help them patch it faster."
76561198011435488,Not Recommended,290340,27545337,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Nyx,"It's hard for me to recommend Armello. While it is undoubtedly very beautiful, the gameplay suffers from several issues, which are only reinforced by quite lengthy matches (it's unlikely that you'll finish in less than an hour, perhaps even longer).The main gripe I have with it is that victory is largely based around luck. Nearly every step of the way you'll enounter it - from card draw to combat to exploring dungeons to whether the damn guard is blocking the path to your next quest. To quests themselves actually - when you finally reach it, you have the option to take the risk and potentially win a reward - an item, a companion or a spirit stone needed for one of the victory conditions. However, if you fail the dice roll, you'll receive a penalty instead.Sometimes you get lucky and the penalty is harmless. Sometimes it's awful. Sometimes you'll be lucky and get the item, other times you will fail despite having damn good odds. It can be very frustrating that way.Every turn you'll encounter situations like these. To me, eventually, that was a deal breaker. Matches became frustrating chore.Oh, and speaking of a chore. For some god forsaken reason you have to unlock most of starting items (you can customize your ""loadout"") by playing the game a lot. It's at least 10 games for each clan to unlock all of their respective items (with last ones arguably being the best across the board, with some exceptions). 4 clans times 10 games times 60 to 90 minutes per match (you can do this in bot matches, though those quickly become boring as hell). I mean at the time of writing I haven't even clocked enough hours in the game to unlock everything, and I'm long done with it.The game also lacks any sort of meaningful communication system, instead opting for Hearthstone-esque chat bubbles. Why would you want to play a board game without being able to talk to the other players I cannot imagine. Due to this, the only form of diplomacy is possible between parties using external software. Teaming up against others is fairly popular in those cases.It's actually astonishing that there are tools in the game to help others (healing items can be used on others, some cards help both caster and castee when used), but no real way to arrange that outside of being in a party.It's not a bad game all in all. Picking it up on sale with a group of friends is probably worth it if you like what this game has to offer. Alone, I would give it a pass.Though you might want to buy it just to take a good look at the gorgeous art alone."
