76561197999439856,Recommended,290340,17939857,"Posted: 8 September, 2015",all,Lagos,"Armello's is a digital board game whose theme is a cocktail of DarkSouls and Game of Thrones, all of it presented with a gorgeous artstyle. Although not especially deep at the moment, it's fun and hasgreat potential for future patches.---Pros:* Art - The art style in this game is absolutely beautiful. The cardsare lovely with their subtle animations and the 2D character art lendsthe heroes a lot of personality. Sound effects and music areappropriate and lovely. I'm looking forward to the DLC at least asmuch for new art and cinematics as I am for new mechanical content.* Fun and Balance - Hard to quantify rigorously, but the game feelsfun - it rewards being thoughtful without demanding that every actionis supremely calculated. Characters feel pretty well balanced giventhe recent release, although not perfectly so. Mechanics likecorruption and the special abilities of followers mean that a singlecard can be applied in different, interesting ways.Cons:* Arbitrary - Serious board game fans should realize that Armello hasa fair amount of luck involved: Drawing the right cards is importantand the outcome of almost all conflicts is dice based (although youmay burn cards to reduce the factor of luck here). However the realelement of luck is in the placement of random events, quests, andperils around the map. You may lose a game due to an unluckypositioning of an early quest or win one because of a timely spiritstone spawn. To win, the rewards from the 'risky' option of quests arevery important, but you'll often have about a 40%-60% chance to failthese, taking an expensive penalty instead. This is particularlynoticeable when two players are both close to victory and thedetermination may hinge on one being a single turn ahead or having alucky/unlucky teleport. It's all fine for a video game, but playersexpecting a more rigorous experience like mageknight or agricola maybe frustrated.* UX Issues - The game permits you to play effects during anopponent's turn, but doesn't offer a good way to pause or an interruptsystem like Magic's. The result is an imperfect blend of real-time andturn-based feels that is jarring at times.  I also experienced are someminor issues in the game such as UI elements disappearing or the soundfailing during certain effects. None of it threatened stability, however.---As for a sense of how the game plays, you spend your turns travelling around the map, preparing yourself through items and quest rewards to face the King, while trying to prevent the other players from doing the same. Usually there are several objectives you could pursue at once (is it worth taking an extra turn to reach my quest if I explore a dungeon first? What about one less turn if I take damage by going through a swamp?) to keep the mind sufficiently tickled. The game has a stronger emphasis on inter-player conflict than board games like Dominion so many of these decisions may involve whether to spend resources pulling yourself up or pushing someone else down.Time factors into all of this. There are a very limited number of turns before the King dies. This introduces conflict between the players pursuing different victory conditions: As the King grows physically weaker over time, a player planning the regicide victory may wish to wait till late to face an easier battle. But if they wait too long and the King dies 'naturally' from his advancing corruption, the current prestige leader will win a diplomatic victory as heir.Overall if you want a beautiful, clever game and don't mind a bit of bad luck, you'll probably like Armello. If nothing else, your eyes will thank you."
,Recommended,290340,18090014,"Posted: 18 September, 2015",all,Dr. Monocle,The thing to remember is that this is a board game brought to vivid life as a computer game. Truly inspired. Can't wait to see what future versions bring.
