,Recommended,290340,30926626,Posted: 3 April,all,Sorbet,"Armello is like that place you've always wanted to visit, because you somehow know that once you're finally there it will feel like home - it will fill a medieval bear sized void in your heart.Before I bought this game I was sceptical for various reasons. I've read most of the reviews on Steam and elsewhere, but  even though it's praised for the incredible visuals (obviously), little is said about the actual gameplay - specifically after the early access release. Also, some of the reviews make it seem like the gameplay is only enjoyable when playing multiplayer.Having now spent the best part of a Sunday playing single player mode I really feel happy about the game.The single player experience is great.The only real story time in the game is a brief tutorial (acting as a prologue) that introduces you to the 4 main characters and the surprisingly easy gameplay mechanics. You *will* find yourself wishing for more, and that's okay, but this is where Armello stays true to being a digital boardgame - you have to make your own story.Brutal deathThe first time a little critter died I was pretty shocked, but then it respawned and all was well with the world. Needless to say you get used to dying... a lot.Again, this game is bloody gorgeousApart from the awesome cut scenes (that's no doubt the thing that caught your attention in the first place), there are over 100 collectable item | spell | trickery cards that are beautifully animated. As you play the game over and over again you discover more and more cards and it becomes quite a challenge to find new ones.LoreThis is a world akin to Brian Jacques' Redwall. It has also been compared to Game of Thrones for some reason... it's probably all the dying and the creepy king. But really this is something quite unique. The collectible cards mentioned before really help to flesh out the world of Armello.According to the developer forum they are planning and actively working on 