76561198019924893,Recommended,290340,23642732,"Posted: 18 June, 2016",all,AI Player 1,"Edit: If you want to see the game in action, I strongly suggest you check out theLeague of Geeks Twitch channelSundays at 6:00pm Pacific time for their weekly Devs vs. Community game. It's a good time and a great place to ask any questions you might have and actually get them answered.Since I bought it back in November, Armello has become one of my all-time favorite multiplayer games (still narrowly beat out by Timesplitters, but what can you do?).Each match is a 4-player free-for-all power grab to rule the land. There are multiple ways to accomplish this:Combat: Break into the Palace and kill the King in single combat.Prestige: Having the most renown when the King dies naturally (he loses 1 health every other turn) or if another players kills him, but dies themselves in the attampt.Spirit StonesCollecting 4 spirit stones that may be found in dungeons, rewarded from quests, or randomly spawned on the map then breaking into the Palace and use them to banish the corruption from the king (which, conveniently, also kills him).Rot: The corrupting force in the game that has infected the king and spurred the heroes into action against him. Though it very difficult to pull off, a player can achieve a higher Rot value than the King and then Break into the Palace and kill the King in combat. This is very similar to a Combat Victory, but when 2 opponents both have Rot, the one with the higher count gains the lower's count as bonus dice. Against the King (who is for the most part a stronger combatant than any of the heroes), this is both a great advantage and hinderance (You roll more dice but for every die you roll that doesn't get matched to attack or defence goes to the King to roll against you). Basically, pulling off a Rot Victory is mostly for bragging rights.My favorite part of this game has to be that, even if the whole game is going against you, the other players attack you, banes attack you, your card draw is terrible, etc. etc. etc, it is still possible to sometimes go for the last-ditch-effort break into the palace and attack the king. At worst, you'll die killing him and give the game to the Prestige leader (or just die, granting the king 1 more health and extending the game for 2 more turns), but there's always the chance that you can kill him and win, turning around a game that had been going against you the whole time, and snatching victory for yourself. These are the wins that are always the most memorable because steamrolling your opponents is only fun so many times. The best victories are astruggle.After every (online/non-private) match, you are given a chance at either a key or chest that, once you have one of both, you can use to unlock new dice skins. Winning has no apparent effect on the drop rates, though keys do seems to be somewhat less common than chests (despite which one you get being represented by a coin flip). The keys, chests, and skins can all be traded/sold on the Steam marketplace.The biggest (non bug related) complaint I have is that, since the map is randomized for every match, sometimes you just get completely screwed on the placements of settlements, dungeons, mountains and swamps (either for too much or not enough of any of them near your spawn grounds).The biggest bug related problem is that sometimes, when a player disconnects, the whole match will feeze and everyone will be forced to quit out, negating the end-of-the-match reward. This seems to be more likely if it happens while someone is in combat, and is definitely the biggest bug/glitch problem the game has.One other point of irritation is, since you can sell the rewards from the end of a match, I occassionally run into bots/scummers that pass every turn (some contend that it is almost literally every match, but I think they're just especially bitter people in general). The especially awful ones spam the emotes constantly. Having one less player usually makes the game significantly less interesting and fun. Furtunately, you can report these wastes of air through the in-game bug report feature.At first it might seem like everything's random so you're success or failure is based solely on RNG, but as a long time player of XCOM (new and original), your success or failure is based more on how you operate with the options you're given, rather than the options themselves.TL;DR: If you think games that rely on RNG don't take any skill, go ahead and skip this one. You'll only wind up bitter."
,Recommended,290340,14138230,"Posted: 23 January, 2015",all,[AoF] TheRedRaccoon,"Updated Aug. 7th, 2015 Review Additions:Over the past few months, I can honestly say this game has made leaps and bounds from where I hopped on. The community continues to grow, the game continues to get better, and I can only imagine what amazing things are in store from its actual release and onward.LoG and the rest of the Armello community are some of the best people I've gotten to know, and every dime spent on this project was well used. I can say with a surety that this game is well worth your money, and that this game is ten-times as good as it was in its Early EA.If you're still unsure about whether or not this game will interest you, I suggest keeping an eye on LoG's twitch channel, and watching the weekly community vs devs games (they're a hoot!).~~~Edited Original Review:So, even after my first match with AI, I can wholeheartedly recommend this game. The TLC that LoG constantly states they've given this game is quite evident, even from the main menu and first few turns. Literally everything in this game works together to create quite a triumphant and easily enjoyed experience that does not disappoint. The art work, fabulous. The music, fantastic. The gameplay, classic, yet new.Performance:I have helped LoG (and continue to help them) squash as many bugs as possible, and I can honestly say that they are rather fast and efficient at getting rid of game bugs. Thankfully this game runs rather well on my lower-mid level laptop. Not to mention that it has a rather low space footprint for a game of this kind.Aesthetics:This game is very pleasing to look at and to listen to. If you don't believe me, you obviously haven't watched the trailers. The trailers alone send shivers down the spine, and leave a considerable amount of chilling goosebumps upon one's person. I sincerely hope that the OST will at some point be available, because it would be an easy buy, even if you don't play the game, for the music, too, plays an integral part in sweeping you away to the magical land that is Armello.Gameplay:Armello is designed to play a lot like a table-top RPG/Card/Board game. Each of the 4 base characters have initial stats and a unique ability, and receive bonuses based on a ring and amulet of the player's choosing. The characters play a large part in how the outcome of the game can be achieved by catering to different playstyles, making the character choice a rather important one - though, not necessarily game-defining. While one can achieve different types of victories with the same character, some conditions are easier met by certain characters.Each turn can easily be a game changer, as players are constantly in a close struggle to gain prestige, gold, magic, or treasure all necessary things to taking the throne, the ultimate objective of the match. There is seldom a point in the game where one can relax, because someone else is almost always on your heels in terms of strength, or physical/magical gains.Experience:This game is rather easy to jump into and enjoy, however, it is highly recommended to look into the game guide here on Steam. Even with its current, early mechanics, this game is easily replayable. Each match and turn is able to bring quite a different experience, and only gets better in a game against other humans. The characters and other pre-match choices can make a large difference based on who's playing who, so the strategizing happens from the get-go.I chose to buy in because this game interested me, and I know that being an Indie Dev is far from easy, and every dollar counts. However, I do again, sincerely hope that this first project doesn't leave a bad taste in the gaming community's mouth because of a mistake made in their infancy (the KickStarter incident, which as since been cleared up!).Pseudo TL;DR -This game is a rather specific purchase...If this is a game you're looking for, I can personally recommend it.For those of you sitting on the fence: Trust me, this game is well worth it, and the community is truthfully one of a kind."
