76561198061732036,Not Recommended,290340,29854923,Posted: 11 February,all,warfighter4,"B.L.U.F.: Armello is a good looking game that mimics tabletop leisure. It can be enjoyed by casual players but, due to the high volume of the game mechanics relying on random chance, players looking for a strategy-based game should avoid it. I would give it a 6 out of 10 for casual gamers but a 2 out of 10 for experienced board game enthusiasts.Why should I play: The game can be fun if not taken seriously.Why should I avoid: Micro-transactions (skins, characters, seasons, dice) -AND- multiple game mechanics that rely on randomness that impede tactics/ strategy.I have found that generally your hero's stats aren't terribly useful in most situations because you are rolling dice and randomness prevails. I have seen discussions on this aspect of the game and many people respond with the pithy ""of course its random, its a board game."" This is a fair assessment, but buyers should purchase with eyes wide open. If you are a fan of games like Risk where you can attack with an army three times the size of your opponent's and still get utterly housed due to bad rolls, then you may enjoy this game. However, if you appreciate games where smart tactics developed to accomplish larger strategic goals are more of a central role to game mechanics, I strongly advise you avoid this game.Here are some other reasons the game misses the mark on being a strategy-based game (all of which are about randomness):Quests: Quests are an easy way for your character to gain a boost to your stats and prestige. They also allow you an opportunity to receive a follower, spirit stone, treasure, etc. The mechanic for whether you receive the bonus or get whacked by a penalty is an odds-based roll. The quest is based on one of your stats and the percentage for your success is based on that stat. For instance, if you have 6 Body and it is a Body quest, you have a 60% chance of being successful. Thus, you can improve your chances, but ultimately its a random 'roll' that dictates reward or punishment. This is interesting but generally there is very little way for you to build your character up to a 100% chance of success.Cards: There is no opportunity to build a deck of cards for your character. You merely pull/draw from a random pile. I will concede that you get the option to draw from three decks (Items, Spells, or Trickery). However, there is a great deal of variation within each deck. The cards you draw may be very useful or downright unhelpful. One could argue that each player has the opportunity to pull the same awful cards and thus it evens out. Point taken. However, this mechanic does not provide any supporting evidence that this is strategy game. Furthermore, this mechanic compounds the overall randomness of the game when coupled with the aforementioned random number generation (RNG) issue seen with the character stats. The cards do provide you an opportunity to ""burn"" them for a chance to influence odds, BUT......Weighting the Odds: There is an interesting mechanic within the game that allows a player to ""burn"" cards to ensure you roll a dice to an outcome that matches the symbol in the top right corner of the card. This is interesting and has great potential. Execution is something to be desired because there is limited flexibility. A character may not wish to play the card for its effect, rather saving it to burn on a combat or peril challenge. Great concept until you come across a card that adds no value for your strategy whether it is used or burned. An example is the often reviled ""Rot"" cards. These cards give your character Rot when played for their effect. Rot can be useless for your character (unless you are going for a Rot victory) or it can be wildly harmful to your strategy in the game. The real problem is that when you burn the card it simply nullifies one of your dice. The kicker is that there is no other way to get rid of that card. You do not get an option to dump it at the end of your turn. To recap this concept, if you pull a rot card and you do not wish to go towards a Rot victory your options are to (1) use it to your own detriment, (2) burn it in a combat or peril challenge to waste a dice, or (3) hold on to the card endlessly and allow it to prevent you from drawing cards you need. Without a discard or 'dump' function within the game, your overall strategy can be hamstrung by cards like this (though to be clear, Rot cards are not the only cards that pose issues to a strategy).Dungeons: Entering a dungeon gives you a chance at receiving gold, gaining more temporary spirit (for casting spells), summoning a bane, receiving a follower, teleporting you to another dungeon, etc. Surprise! I won't belabor the point on this aspect - this is another random mechanic within the game.Other Random nonsense:""Wait....what?There is more? warfighter4, how can this be? I thought 4 major game mechanics that relied on randomness would be sufficient?"" Nay, my friend. One of my favorite instances of randomness within the game is a follower you can pick up from a dungeon who is named ""The Stranger."" This plague joins your hero and then moves you by one hex, randomly, at the start of your turn. You have no way to get rid of this 'follower' (that somehow LEADS your hero in the direction of his choosing) unless you get right next to another hero. You wanna know an interesting tid-bit, friend? The Stranger doesn't leave automatically when you get next to another hero. He determines whether he comes or goes based on ..... wait for it.... randomness. Thus you can tweak your turn-based tactics to get within range of another hero to get rid of this pied-piper, but there is no guarantee that he will leave."
