76561198044110464,Recommended,290340,17952629,"Posted: 8 September, 2015",all,Calavontis,"Nice game.I like it.  A very good product of a designed based on hybridizing board/dice/card games with RPG / 4x-esque games.  It might be a bit too oversimplified, but deeper strategies do exist.My favorite part about the game (and the part in which I think it does the best) is its job of developing and presenting the theme.  The artwork, the lore, the presentation of the entire story (which is unforutnatly a bit short) was very well done.  The win conditions are all very fitting, from slaying the king in direct combat to submitt oneself to the corrupting Rot, it all goes with the lore very nicely.  At the end of each game you can pretty much imagine a tale written about what happened in the past 1 or 2 hour of gameplay, as the mechanic of the game trasnlates into a story smoothly.Now the gameplay in itself is not bad at all.  People say it is too luck dependent, but really it's just a factor you stratgize around.  The actual range of risk analysis isn't so big.  Sure, rollin 4 dice might sometime beat someone who is rolling 6, but that should be in your consideration of margin of risk and possiblity.  Engagment with dice differentiation of 4 or more is rarely unexpected.  Furthermore, the overall health of all the character is relatively low in comparsion too all the things that can kill you.  It's more often than not that both combatants just die from fighting than one guy winning purely due to chance.  The only thing that is bit too chancy is quests and spirit stones.  Although they normally don't change the outcome too much, it's a weird mechanic of odds with a payoff that doens't really makes much sense.In other words, the game has set a very good premise on this hybrid genre.  It has a good base, a great art form, phenomonial theme and lore.  All it needs is to expand on the mechanics, extend compaign story, rework the chance mechanics a little.  I hope they can pack a lot of more good content in a DLC or something, because otheriwse there would be little incentive to keep working on the same game.8/10 for novelty.  10/10 if you are big on thematic and artistic elements."
76561197996754375,Recommended,290340,17916893,"Posted: 6 September, 2015",all,Skammunist Manifesto,S'purdy fun.
76561198155714516,Recommended,290340,17935287,"Posted: 7 September, 2015",all,whitehyena357,"In short: This is a charming game. It's fun, it's replayable, and it's nice to look at.But if you like reading longer reviews -Armello is a turn-based strategy roleplay game, built much like one would build a board game. In fact, I would go as far as to call this a, 'Virtual Boardgame'. The gameplay is exactly what you'd expect from that: Rolling dice, moving tiles, drawing cards, and collecting stuff, until you can claim victory, or the timer runs out. Gameplay is a bit repetitive, but you certainly don't play Monopoly because of the ways you can innovate. There are several ways to aquire victory; some of which are somewhat hard, and there are playstyles that show through that. It's very hard to secure a 'Rot' victory, but fairly easy to accumulate prestige, and simply wait the timer out.I really like the art style, and I am a big fan of the 'furry' theme. Don't worry, non-furs, there's no Yiffing here. It's visually appealing, and the music matches what's going on on the board very well, as well as helping to really immerse you in the game. Though, I wouldn't exactly say that the soundtrack alone is worth half the game's pricetag, (at a whopping $9.99 at the time of this review) it definitely helps my score. It's very moving, and flowing, and keeps a light-hearted tone until the grim of battle finds you for the first time.Overall, I have to give the game a 8/10, marred only by the steep pricetag, and a lack of a campaign."
76561197991610654,Recommended,290340,17952462,"Posted: 8 September, 2015",all,Aceritas,"Its sad I cant share my actual Armello stories. Some of them have been pretty good.Pick one of 8 heroes, each from one of four clans. Wolf, Bear, Rat, or Rabbit. Chose the ring and amulet that will give them special, clan specific, bonuses. On top of the heroes unique ability. Then begin the quest to become King or Queen of Armello. The king will succumb to the Rot a little after a week. Depending on certain choices made before day 9. Or the king defeats a few would be heroes.Chose cards based on three types. Trickery, that may require gold, or prestiege. Magic, wich requires the magic resource to use. Or Items, requiring gold. Each type may also cause corruption. Corrupted weapons, magic, and trickery will cause the user to contract Rot. Becoming corrupted has its own benefits and drawbacks. And is one of the four ways to claim the throne. You could also win by being prestige leader. By combat. Or by spirit stone, and banish the king. Its never clear how you will win each game. Or who will ultimately become the next ruler of Armello.Positives:+ Nice artstyle+ Neat game and dice mechanics+ 4 different ways to win+ No two games play exactly alike+ Immersive music+ Procedurally generated maps, no two maps are exactly the same+ Interesting and animated cards+ Addicting, reminds me of hearthstone in a way+ Can still use cards, even if it isnt your turn+/- Luck plays a big part in some games, epic underdog wins happen.Negatives- Only 8 characters currently, the amount of heroes feels small- Maps only have one size & cannot be changed, currently- Games are short, only four-ish quests can be done before the king dies- No animation skips, you have to watch the AI's turns.- No team game modes. A Clan Vs. Clan would be fun, like the Rabbit Clan versus the Rat Clan.After playing for a few hours, I dont mind losing, the adventure, challenges, choices, chances, and rewards in each playthrough keep me hooked. Each game tells a story it feels like. And the music and art can get pretty immersive.And Im used to playing bloody metal shooters like Killing Floor2. Another good game, if you are wondering.Armello is great,Buy It/10"
