,Recommended,290340,26740354,"Posted: 21 November, 2016",all,TheMightyCthulhu,"If you enjoy board games (not Monopoly or Risk, but real board games), you'll enjoy Armello. It reminds me a bit of a simplified Mage Knight (board game) or Runebound. It's addictive good fun, so long as you don't mind random elements like card draws and dice rolls. If you go into the game appreciating it for what it is, and not expecting every element to be skill based, you'll have a blast. I don't think it's fare to give the game negative reviews simply because you didn't know what it was going into it.While there are random elements to the game you have no control over, there is still a large amount of strategy and skill. From hex movement and board control, to skillful usage of card playing and 'burning' cards in combat, to equipping your character before and during the game... there is a lot to it.The animated 2D art is absolutely fantastic - the cards and the (too few) cut scenes are beautiful, the 3D board itself is fairly meh. The character designs are great (I'm especially fond of River's design and Sana's design), and their implimentation in 3D is the best aspect of the 3D elements of the game.I would recommend the game to anyone that enjoys colourful art, doesn't mind spending an hour or an hour and a half playing a game based roughly 50/50 on skill and chance, and that likes board games."
