76561198032386971,Recommended,290340,15175605,"Posted: 2 April, 2015",all,rigsby,"As someone who rarely purchases games, I am very pleased that I decided to invest in Armello.The whole game oozes charm and elegance with lovely graphics and a flowing soundtrack that fits perfectly with the mood of the moment. It features some old ideas but executes them so that they feel new and original.The game can be played straight from the box but, as the player gets more involved, the various strategies and mechanics become clearer. Do you strive for strength in close combat or opt for tiptoeing around the world, searching for spirit stones, and using long-range tactics to shatter your opponents?I love the way this game has been designed. It has the power to immerse and captivate you with plenty of variation and scope for future expansion. Each of the heroes provide a different approach to winning the game and can be further defined by completing quests and obtaining a wide range of useful objects like armour, spells and follower companions. The element of luck and random outcomes makes every game different and entertaining.If you enjoy employing your brain, I think you'll really like Armello!"
76561198025301143,Recommended,290340,15243339,"Posted: 6 April, 2015",all,GoshanX,"I've always been a board game fan, and had both high expectations and trepidation walking into Armello. Would the RPG element be complete enough? Would the game be deep enough in a one hour play through? Would it be exciting enough to get me to play it over and over?  More importantly, would I ever choose to play Armello when I could otherwise play Settlers of Catan or Dominion on my kitchen table?The answer is YES, to all of these questions.The RPG element is too downplayed to really be called ""RPG"". It is more ""inspired by"" RPG. The closest thing I can think of to it is Munchkin—the RPG parody. Yes, you go around and get treasures and equip weapons, but the real reason for doing this is to get a strategic advantage, not just to make yourself more badass. The advantages are sufficient that you are encouraged to quest not because the quest is interesting (it's not) but because if you can complete it, you'll be one step farther than your opponents to achieving late game dominance.In terms of game mechanics and win conditions, the latest update, Engines of Fate, has greatly improved the chances that trying for another victory condition other than a prestige (points) victory could nab you the win. Better, even if they don't, trying for another victory condition could give you the advantage you need in the late game to lock down a prestige victory as a fall back. It is this full-game strategy that makes Armello worth playing. Once the full version is released, I expect that this to be an extremely replayable game, and a refreshing change from most turn-based video games like Civilization that take most of a day or longer to play."
