,Recommended,290340,15227137,"Posted: 5 April, 2015",all,Total War Lion,"Let me give you the TL;DR first for those of you wanting a quick review.Excellent game, beautiful graphics, challenging and fun. The price tag is acceptable for the gameplay presented (and I'm incredibly picky about price vs. quality). Oh, and I ran this on a painfully bad laptop and it still looked and ran flawlessly.Cons: for those who button mash, jump blindly into things or have no patience, you're going to have a steep learning curve ahead of you because the game requires strategy. No compendium of spells/items/trickeries for review and future planning (though this does give the game an element of think-on-your-feet strategy).Final ruling: Worth buying, especially for the multiplayer.Now, let me go into a bit of a lengthier review, I'm reviewing this game while it is in-dev, and while I usually don't leave a review, I feel that I should definitely give this game some credit and accolades. First off, beautiful game, as I said before. I ran this game on a computer that failed to meet two of the specs in the initial screen and it still ran without a single hitch and lag so minor that itmaybeadded on 10 seconds to my overall game. What I'm getting at here is that the game is incredibly user friendly.In playing the game through with each of the characters once, their traits are balanced so that you have a fair chance to win with each character, though you still have to win with strategy, as blindly rushing the king will more than likely help your opponent achieve victory. Took me a second to realize that to activate cards I had to drag and hold, but after I realized this I also came to the conclusion that whoever made this mechanic is a lovely person who didn't want us to have to click yes in an 'Are you sure you want to do this?' popup box hundreds of times.I'll give further review as the game develops and adds in new features, but for an in-dev and early access game, it already has me quite happy and eagerly awaiting further releases."
