,Recommended,290340,25435135,"Posted: 9 September, 2016",all,ReusedNPCv2,"Everyone loves a party game - take some frenemies, a whole bunch of dice, and a competitive setting, and let the salty, salty blood flow. Games like Talisman, for example, or your pick of most all physical board games. Enter Armello, another game to scratch that itch. And I for one think it does that admirably.The gameplay mechanics are a bit complex, but easy to understand after a few games or playing the in-game tutorial settings. The game itself is thoroughly enjoyable, and I've personally enjoyed every game I've played insofar.That said, this brand of multiplayer isn't for everyone. Those who aren't on speaking terms with Lady Luck need not apply, nor those who don't enjoy losing to a fluke of RNG. As with most of this sort of game, the catch is in the chaos.The game's graphics are superb, and all the art is well-illustrated (more or less). The art style is something to behold, and all the animations are fluid. Even the rolls of the dice are something else. All the card arts are animated, as well.In summary, if you like chaotic games of chance, Armello is for you. Go on, pick it up.And as a footnote: If you really like this game, you can turn a profit off of it. Yes, you read that right. After every match you get a chest or a key which I'm told is worth around $0.25. Mind, I personally use them to try for dice skins, but perhaps you're not so into cosmetics."
