76561197994288195,Recommended,290340,22227629,"Posted: 3 April, 2016",all,twyman.alex,"An addictive digital board game that will usurp the dwindling hours of the night that, foolishly, you thought you could spare. Play til 10pm, because of work the next morning? Why not, instead, zone out and play until it is 3am and lazily muffle a curse out of your lethargic lips when you realise you sacrificed a good nights sleep for a few hours of strategic maneuvers under the fate of a dice roll. Then, whilst you prepare to sleep, you can debate the role and function of free will and determinism, or just god damn luck based compatibilism. However your argument pans out, be sure as you're going to be grumpy in the morning, that at least Armello was saved from a King ridden with Rot.Until you play again. But of course, only until 10pm.The mechanics of the game work seamlessly, and the fluid deck building dynamic adds individuality into each game ensuring a reasonable element of uniqueness for each session of kingdom saving joy.The writers have clearly gone into great length into writing stories for the optional (and recommended) quests that you perform each game, but I fear that those poor scribes have worked in vain, for it is not a story dependent game (however, I for one found it extremely charming, and appreciate the effort - it's just that it is not integral to the actual joy of the game. If you are to take my opinion on this matter, you must take in stock that I have read most, if not all, of the in-game books from the Elder Scrolls series, Morrowind and up. What am I doing with my life? God knows, but ‘He basically read meta-fiction in games and enjoyed manly solitary one-handed pleasures’ wouldn't be the most untruthful epitaph I'd have scribed on the marble above me)I would say it is a short lived novelty game, and I don't think I'd be completely wrong. I have stacked up 50 hours on this sucker in a short amount of time though, and that is due to the relatively small time you need to invest into any single game. It is by this virtue that makes it a remarkable digital board game. Hell, if you were of the creatively productive type, you could fashion tiles out of cardboard, make painted clay figurines, print out cards, make some dice, and successfully play this with offline friends (there was a time in humanity where we socialised amongst fleshy alterations of ourselves, believe me or not. Back then, we just called those people 'friends'. But they became tiresome and didn't have numbers or pop cultural references in their monikers, and their avatars were what we called 'faces').Basically, you choose between four different species (Bear, Wolf, Rabbit, Rat), who in turn, have two variations that centre on their particular strengths and abilities (Wizard, Warrior, Diplomat, Rogue). With that, you choose stat perks and bonuses. Then you're thrown into the game. You compete with three other souls to try focus on one of the game victory conditions. It's not too difficult to grasp, but would be redundant to type here as it is explained competently in the game description and the developers website (which is charming in itself, I implore you to explore it yourself).Either way, cracking game in its simplicity and its uniqueness. Go have at it.Or don't.I'd rather you did though. Needs more players active for multiplayer, and I don't have the time and energy to replicate a physical board game, nor acquire friends.Enjoy, you magnificent people.For Armello."
