76561198077512080,Recommended,290340,31874624,Posted: 20 May,all,Celleron,"When I saw this game at a distance in videos it reminded me of Civilizations, which isn't a game I liked. After some months of my friends playing I decided to give it a try and learned I should of gotten it sooner. I play almost always with friends we all have our prefered heroes but some always play on a whim. Even picking a hero there is so many ways to play them, River can do quests, get HRW, and snipe the king; or she can play to stealth and snipe Banes/Heroes to gain prestige for the win. Still a lot to learn of finer details but I am glad to have a PvP game that doesn't induce stress but brings out the fun of RNG that rivals that of Mario Party. I often see plenty of complaints about the game having errors but have yet to see one myself, all the same if you have friends who enjoy board games then get this and laugh the night away as Sylas goes on a murder spree, tearing through a couple players and a guard to just be banished the second he enters the palace."
76561198006973479,Recommended,290340,31732171,Posted: 13 May,all,Matticus Caesar,"If you enjoy board games & RPGs, like animals, and are fascinated by the intrigues, stand-offs, and backstabbing in Game of Thrones, then there is no reason for you not to own this game. Most games of Armello will last between 60-90 minutes depending on a wide array of factors. I've also played one game that barely went 40 minutes and another that went well over 2 hours.The game's art may come off as cartoony and possibly even childish, but don't be fooled for a minute; there is a very dark and scheming underbelly to Armello. There are numerous roads to victory, none of them particularly simple, and different heroes may have an easier time pursuing one path versus another. I have often found that starting a game with one strategy in mind often falls apart very quickly depending on the play styles of your opponents and what cards come out. It really helps to understand your chosen hero's abilities, strengths, and weaknesses and how they may succeed or fail against your different opponents as you go along (your and everyone else's ""character sheets"" are always available for viewing in game).Try the different clan heroes out and learn the mechanics in single player mode, but at some point definitely play multiplayer - that is where the real fun & intrigue of this game lies.One feature I like is the ability to watch another player's battles and peril challenges. You click on an icon and you can watch what cards are drawn, who the dice get rolled, etc.I think the third video in the Steam ads for this game captures the essence of Armello the best - the one that starts with ""From great horrors, great heroes emerge."" Every game begins in a similar demeanor... the players tend to all greet each other, but within 3 or 4 turns it all turns delightfully ugly because in the end, just like in The Highlander, ""There can be only one.""I think you will find Armello is an extremely satisfying game experience in a maddening sort of way. $20 very well-spent."
