,Not Recommended,290340,18193288,"Posted: 25 September, 2015",all,Paint Paw,"So What can I say about this game so I'll just start with my issues with the games 'features'-Easy to play, hard to master: Which is just another way of saying luck decides the winner. No matter how hard you try and outwit your enemy no matter how far you're in the lead one bad dice roll at a critical moment and you lose the game just like that. There really is only 2 valid strategies for each character which in turn is just different executions of the same two win conditions, either kill the king or drag the game out in what is in all essence winning by default or through cowardice( getting an early prestige lead and play keep away until someones low on health). The third win condition which is to clense the king is PURE luck that you get 4 stones before he dies of rot.-It's so called fast and thoughtful gameplay is lacking in both departments. With the amount of luck that the game is based on a 'thoughtful' strategy could just be crossing your fingers and hope the king doesn't B.S. his way into killing you. The game is no way fast-paced with 4 players each getting two turns a day before the king loses 1 health, if by fast paced they ment you constantly get killed because many things are out of control( which is why strategy is weak).-Multiply playable Heroes: but you don't get all the playable heroes unless you kickstarted the game $55, I would've been fine if the Heroes were just alternate skins of the 8 your given, but they aren't they are unique heroes just like the base ones, which is absolutely infuriating when they plan to add the 4 later as payed dlc. To put this in perspective its the same as a fighting game releasing with 12 characters, but 4 are only accessible if you preorder for twice the price of the game and they become dlc later in the year, but were on disc at the launch so you're just being baited into paying more for the rest of the game.Their physics-based dice look nice at first but like actual dice they will fall off the play area and you only know about the reroll at the last minute.The world of the board game is bland which makes sense for a board game, but when people try to call this an rpg, and a turn-based strategy it's like getting slapped in the face.In the long and narrow of this review: if they can actually make the game develop into something where luck isn't the omni-present factor to the game. I might get a second look at the game."
