,Recommended,290340,18334967,"Posted: 4 October, 2015",all,agentx,"This is a fantastic game and I'm following any supplementary material that gets released in the future.Pros:-Every game has enough variety so it never gets old-The game is fluid enough that it's possible to change your entire strategy before endgame if needed-Well-balanced characters-Good balance of luck and strategy-Fantastic art and fluid animation-Original world building. While there's a clear Redwall influence, it's definitely its own unique universeCons:/-Inability to view the entire map- scrolling around to find your quest is frustrating-Have to buy four copies to play multiplayer with friends-No free form chat. All the chat options are preselected, making clear communication in multiplayer almost impossible.Comments:-There's a significant amount of luck involved, but with a fertile mind you can turn even strokes of bad luck to your advantage. Apparently there's official backstories, but I can't find the sources online so if anyone knows where to find them, please drop me a line."
,Recommended,290340,19348078,"Posted: 28 November, 2015",all,Patralex,"Armello is certainly an interesting game, to say the least.We'll start with the story:Armello is a land plague by The Rot, a corruption that feeds on life force. Playing through the prologue gives you a wonderful tutorial, as well as the enjoyable story itself.Gameplay:The game itself is unique, differing from turn-based stragetgy games like Sid Meier's Civilization by adding a dice system. Players can burn cards to ensure they get a roll they like for single dice, and roll the rest, randomly getting fighting results. In addition, you can customize your battles and dice rolls with Equipment cards, and your Party cards.While turns can take a little while, you do have the ability to play cards from your hand during anybody's turn, dealing damage, laying traps, or buffing your own hero. The game generally has a dusk/dawn system, with the game generally ending at the 10th Dawn. Each player acts during the dawn phase, then the time rolls over to dusk, where turns reset, granting new advantages between day and night cycles. The game gets a little repetitive after several games, with only 8 heros to choose from. The tile-randomization on the map is helpful, as well as the starting trinkets you choose to buff your character, but unless new heros are added soon, you might quickly find yourself bored. Multiplayer can provide a different challenge from the story mode AI, and is generally similar to Civ V in that respect. It's fun, but may not be for everybody.Graphics and Sound:The soundtrack is beautiful to listen to, and is relaxing to listen to. The sounds that play during character animations are pleasant as well, and very suiting, especially with the game's art style. The artwork of the game is beautiful. Cards have animated graphics, Heros and NPCs alike have unique animations. The cartoony and furry-esque themed style is adorable, and can easily captivate those who find fluffy creatures cute.OVERALL, I'd recommend getting this game, especially when it's on sale, although I feel the $20 pricing is justified. The game is fun, but it does need a tad more content -- namely, a few more cards and heroes would be nice."
