76561197972398779,Recommended,290340,20411135,"Posted: 8 January, 2016",all,Ashambles,"Armello is a fun, relaxed strategy game, one of those whose rules are relatively simple to grasp, but that allows for a number of viable strategies to emerge. I like it because a multiplayer game takes from 45 minutes to an hour or so to play, making it a good way to relax at the end of a workday or when downtime presents itself. Each of the heroes feels fairly well balanced; although some dominant strategies have emerged in multiplayer games, smart players have multiple ways to disrupt one another's pursuit of the throne. In single player games, the AI is competent, and it's a good way to experiment with different streategies, although the true meat of the game is multiplayer. The art is fantastic and the music quite nice.If you can't stand losing a strategy game due to the luck of the die or the draw of the card, this one might not be for you. Because of these random elements, it's difficult to come into a game with a solid strategy, and adapatability is required. If you could customize your card deck, a more reliable strategy might be possible. For me, these elements are not a problem. Another downnside to the game at this point (Jan 2015) is that it can be difficult at times to find partners for a skirmish match. It would be nice to be able to fill out a random group with an AI player or two as you can in private games.I hope in the near future we'll see ranked multiplayer, bringing a sense of progress to multiplayer games. In the meantime, Armello remains a great way to realx with a lite but challenging turn-based strategy game."
