,Recommended,290340,28176944,"Posted: 3 December, 2016",all,I Aten't Dead,"I love board games. I play a metric ♥♥♥♥ ton of them. So a game about animals with a cutesy (AMAZING) art style mixed with the bitter taste of medieval RPG politics makes for a sweet spicy blend. I just struggle to really commend it beyond that.Armello is all about becoming the King or Queen of the land as the former King - as wonderful as he was - is slowly falling into madness due to a particularly painful corruption that's slowly killing him. No matter what happens, this lovable scamp's going to be dead in about 8 days give or take. Your job is to take his place, either through political sway or the incredibly direct route. As for the game itself, it's a matter of going on quests to gain additional stat points which will lead to boosting your chances of victory. Sounds simple enough right? Well, it is, which makes Armello an easy game to pick up and play. But it also leads to one of its failings.Armello is a game where 80% is decided by luck, not your tactics, but by card draws and dice rolls. ""Oh no"" you say, player of Armello, ""there are plenty of tactics in place to boost your chance for victory!"" to which I reply ""you are very right, you just need to draw those cards."" At the beginning of your turn, you draw up to your hand limit (measured by the stat Wits) from three different decks. Items are all about things that boost your character, whether that's combat, perils, health, etc. Spells range from offensive magic to play on rivals to stat and combat boosts. Trickery cards are all about messing with the flow of the game, creating traps and making political moves. You could get the cards from the Trickery deck that would allow you to create obstacles for your rivals, but you need to draw them. You could instead draw cards that create pacts with others, or offer other abilities which will do you no good. Or you could draw exactly the right cards and just annihilate your hapless foe before they even get a turn. Thankfully there is a balance as more powerful cards are less plentiful and more expensive to play, but nothing says you can't just draw three of these cards in a row and suddenly go from last place to first place.""Alright,"" you say ""but what does dice have to do with this?"" Oh I'm glad you asked. Cards may give you the means to control the game, but dice decide your ultimate fate in Armello. There is a sword, shield, sun, moon, rot, and wyld side to every die. In combat, swords are brought into a total to decide your overall attack, shields mark your defense against an opponent's attack or counter-attack, sun and moon are added to your attack depending on the time of day and count as misses if it's not currently that time of day, and finally wylds and rots are explosive attack dice. If you're playing a normal game of Armello, every wyld will be an attack and then become a free die to instantly reroll to see if you do more damage or take less damage and rots count as misses. If you're corrupt from rot (the local corruption) - and this is harder than you think to do - then rots instead count as attacks that become additional dice and wylds become misses. As you may have noticed, there are only two ways to avoid taking damage from an enemy, rolling enough shields or hoping your opponent rolls enough misses. Dice could say that your hero with seven dice will lose in battle to a hero with two dice because they happen to roll wyld after wyld and suddenly they've rolled eight dice while half of your rolls were misses. Explosive dice also roll over to perils, which are obstacles on the map that you can overcome by - you guessed it - rolling dice to match the correct symbols. Perils however are determined by different stats, there are wits perils and spirit perils, the higher these amounts, the better defense you have.""Hold on!"" you now demand, pointing rapidly, ""these aren't set in stone, they can be modified by getting item cards to boost the amount of dice you get or increasing shields and swords without dice!"" Alright, notice you just said cards. So, again, let me remind you, what decrees that you will ever get these cards? Luck does. The most strategy that cards and dice give you is the ability to burn cards in battle to give the symbol on the card to one of your dice. Since you refill to your hand limit every turn, there's very little reason to why you shouldn't burn through as much of your hand as you can every turn so there's a better chance of drawing better cards. However, again, you need to draw these cards to give the correct symbols for your dice. So even this strategy is mandated by a level of luck. Really I could go on, but I think you get the point.Armello is still a good game. I might have ripped it apart for being so luck based, but it's still a game I played over 20 hours of and still enjoy playing. Artistically the game is impressive, and thematically it feels truly alive. Since the game has minimal strategy, games (and turns) are short and intense, befitting of the game's brutal nature, you're invested enough to want victory but still distanced enough to not really care if you lose. It's just a game after all, and in minutes you can start a new one. As I've played Armello, I've discovered strategies on how to best manipulate the game to my advantage, despite all the luck involved. And even now, the developers add new things to the game to increase replayability and balance things out. So I feel like while the game does have its flaws and always will, there are ways to change the game and make it at least a little less luck dependant (ESPECIALLY FOR A ROT VICTORY, HINT HINT).So I want to stress this again, Armello is a good game and is worth your time and money. If you're a more casual board game player or curious about board gaming at all, then you will love Armello, but if you're someone like me who likes their games with minimal luck then you're either going to need to find another game or adjust. Just like the world of Armello, the game is beautiful and well constructed, but hides an undeniable ugliness that you may not spot right away. It's a matter of if you're going to let that ugliness ruin your experience, or be something to overcome.Armello is recommended and will sit best if you have friends to play with or if you get this game on sale."
76561197972529883,Recommended,290340,29229692,Posted: 13 January,all,The Judge,"I amost never write reviews, but this game is such a gem I feel compelled to spread the word.So far, I've played 623 hours and am still not tired of the game. The multiplayer is the best aspect, since there is now a ranking system and prizes. After every game, players receive either a chest or key. Once you have both, you open the chest to receive a set of dice (ranked white, green, blue, purple and orange--like MMO loot). The dice can sell for a good chunk of change on the marketplace, and I was able to pay for the expansion with nothing but my profits from selling extra dice.I feel this game isn't that well known, but there is a committed player base so finding a multiplayer match usually never takes more than a few minutes. It's a slower paced game that stresses strategy over twitch reflexes, which I enjoy. While there are random elements, a good player knows how to mitigate losses and be flexable enough to win. I would compare it to poker--randomness is an element, but good players find ways to win consistently.Overall, I would recommend this game to anyone who enjoys strategy or board games. Hope to see you in game!"
