76561198046941522,Recommended,290340,34102738,Posted: 8 August,all,noelwym,"When I was a young boy, I had a love for board games but the problem was, having only one uninterested sister meant that I was to play alone for most of the time. I have kept this love with me since then and now, I am happy to say that I've some love for the digital board game that is Armello.If you love board games that aren't too simple like Candyland nor too complex like Axis & Allies, Armello is the game for you. In some sense, Armello is like RISK. The dice can make the game or break it for you, but your strategy determines how fast you can exploit or recover from whatever shenanigans the dice result in. There's never really a single path to victory and the best victories are the most unorthodox ones.Now, aesthetically, the game is a pleasing sight to the eyes. In terms of graphics, the game does well enough, and the score goes along with it. The art and animation for the cards are actually quite nice to look at, I have more than once actually visited the Card Gallery to admire the hard work put into them. The presence of anthropomorphic characters is of no concern to me, being long exposed to anthropomorphic in the media thanks to Disney and childhood cartoons. One critique I will reserve for the game at the time of writing though is the lack of lore for too many of the heroes. It's quite inconsistent. Among the Generation Two heroes, only Zosha has a backstory and the Usurpers get no stories at all. The Generation One heroes' backstories are very short blurbs whereas the Bandit Clan heroes get paragraphs of interesting details. Why the inconsistency? Did the lore-writers run out of ideas?Also, pricing. Actually, I'm fine with the pricing. I have played many hours of it to make up for the price tag and the suggestion that the game is behind a paywall isn't that reasonable, considering the 8 non-DLC heroes are nowhere near crutched. You can win as easily with them as you can with the DLC heroes. That said, if you want to make your money's worth, wait for the game and its DLC to go on sale before buying them all. Could save a pretty penny or two."
,Recommended,290340,24762894,"Posted: 7 August, 2016",all,Karunamon,"EDIT 9/2/16A custom feature now exists that provides a great deal of control over the victory conditions! Games can now be as long or as short as you want, and some of the more contentious mechanics can be modified or disabled outright.Very well done, and kudos to the developers! This removes one of my main issues with the game, and changes my review from a ""don't buy"" to a ""buy"". I'm still a bit peeved that the prologue sets up a grand universe that's really just a neat board game, but now that it can be customized, I'm less bothered about it.The original review remains below, unaltered.OverviewThis game is beautiful, and perhaps that's actually some of the problem. You play through the prologue, and you get this very slick, almost Civilization-esque board game laid out for you piece by piece, with a very fleshed out and stylish world. Very nice.But then, you go to play a game, and you find out that no, there's no story, and in addition, a single game cannot be any longer than 9 rounds. One of the mechanics is that whoever has the most influence points when the 9th round is over automatically wins (barring the occasional edge case). 9 rounds goes by in a hurry, and the game is over much faster if any of the other victory mechanics are achieved.It feels like they missed the boat here. I personally can't recommend this game due to violated expectations. The talk of ""role playing"" in the game's description? Almost deceptive.If you go into it knowing that all you're getting is a board game, with the story being a paper thin framing device, then you may be able to enjoy Armello. Otherwise, you may end up disappointed. Decide accordingly.The Good+ Beautiful and atmospheric. You can tell a lot of love went into this title.+ There's nothing wrong with short games per se; it's great way to kill an hour or so with some friends.The Bad- Cap of 9 rounds per game, and this cannot be modified by the player. Certain rare game actions will cause this to be extended, but this is rare.- Games end too quickly- More luck than skill based- Any strategy you'd like to play (perhaps trading off a character's strenghts and weaknesses) is stuck behind an inane achievement-based unlockable system.The Ugly* Realizing that the grand story laid out in the prologue never goes anywhere - it's just a way to frame the tutorial. There is no campaign.* Realizing that the biggest annoyance with this game (the 9 round limit) could be trivially patched out, giving a lot more replay value, and the developers won't do it.OverallToo short, too expensive. Armello is like an ice cream sundae from a very fancy restaurant - looks beautiful on the plate, tastes amazing, but at the end, you're left wanting for more, and wondering why you paid what you did."
