,Not Recommended,290340,34819602,Posted: 8 September,all,hitt.william,"4/10Armello is a multiplayer, turn-based, board-game experience that has been translated to a digital medium. In essence, each player is attempting to solve the problem of a sick king. He's been infected with ""rot,"" and becomes weaker every turn until he dies. You can win in three different ways:1. You can accumulate ""prestige"" by completing quests. If you have the highest prestige upon the king's death, you take his place.2. You can slay the king, simply by being strong in combat. Additionally, if you have accumulated rot yourself, this can aid you in the battle.3. You can accumulate four spirit stones, and use these to cure the king of his malady.Most of the game consists of traversing along a tile-based map attempting to reach your ""quests,"" which appear randomly across the map. In the meantime, you can equip items (most of which aid you in combat), cast spells, or use ""trickery"" cards that seem to represent political schemes.The sheer randomness of the game and some troubling design decisions led me to almost never enjoy myself while playing this game with my friends. First of all, some of the cards are tremendously powerful and can sway the game  substantially.Within the game, there are settlements that a player can capture to increase the amount of gold you receive per turn. Typically, there is no drawback to having as many settlements as possible and it is a good policy to capture as many as you can as you traverse the map. However, one card in the game causes a player to lose ""prestige"" equal to the number of settlements they currently possess. I once lost four prestige (a tremendous amount) being on the receiving end of this card.Another card, a pact, allows two players to each gain one prestige per turn as long as both of the players live. Perhaps this is meant to put a target on these characters, but this card has never entered play without tremendously altering the course of the game. Typically, this card puts the two characters in the pact 4-5 prestige above every other player.In most games, due to random events and cards, I am unable to even complete two of the quests assigned to my character. Between deaths, bane spawns (rot dragons that emerge from dungeons), and perils (challenges that players must complete when landing on certain tiles), I can't even get across the map. This emotion, feeling a lack of both competency and agency, sours every experience I have with the game.This is not even getting into how targeting is unclear, how one character can complete one of the extremely difficult perils in the king's courtyard and ""clear the way"" for another player to waltz into the final battle with the king, how spirit stones are sometimes far too easy to acquire with random spawns, or how the player needs to commit suicide on banes (rot dragons) to stand a chance of achieving a rot score comparable to the king's.The game is charming, with a great visual style, production values, and no multiplayer connection issues. However, this is where my praise for the game ends."
76561198012485592,Recommended,290340,35233829,Posted: 26 September,all,Duncan Idaho,"In Armello, League of Geeks have created a wonderfully textured digital board game.  You play as an animal avatar against three others seeking the throne of a blighted King who will die in a set number of turns until you vanquish him or gain enough prestige to be awarded the throne on his death.   The King is both competitor and game master, visiting proclamations that affect gameplay each dawn (the gameboard has a day/night cycle and this also affects gameplay in various ways with certain events, cards and equipment operative only during either cycle).  The Kings ""guard"" (appropriately loyal dogs) and Banes, crow-like monsters, also appear on the game board to variously attack players, defend the King or carry out his insane proclamations, adding complexity to the game.Armello's production values are quite high, especially the card artwork (the inventory/spell/peril cards are extraordinarily well-rendered and the artists are credited which is a nice touch).  Animations, sound, music and board visuals are all colorful and engaging.It will take a few playthoughs to get a sense of the various victory pathways (hint: go for prestige victories at first, they are the easiest).  Avatars have enough distinguishing stats and traits, which, along with various jewelry choices at avatar set up make for somewhat unique builds (although those looking for deep, RPG-style customization will be disappointed).   The player must manage the gameboard's topography (with various tiles affecting movement, health and offering exploration benefits), equipment choices, perils (a symbol matching affair versus negative effect), quest system and - of course - dice-based combat.  Combat in particular is quite satisfying with tactile dice rolls including beautifully rendered dice and sound effects.  Various dice apply various offensive or defensive bonuses, explode into additional dice or count as misses.  I was surprised how much excitement the battles generate.Armello has enough complexity to create solid replay value even in the base game (which this review pertains to).   In single play, a game can take 20-30 minutes, although you can speed up AI turns if you wish.  It's probably best to keep the game at regular speed as a beginner as it really pays to study your opponents' choices.   Multiplayer plays quite a bit longer (human players generally take longer to make their turn choices, equip inventory and study the game board, etc.); as a result, I had a few players quit my game such that by the end I was playing the AI.Quite a few negative reviews cite the randomness of many events of the game (not sure why this surprises/enrages some people as it is a board game and such games notoriously rely on dice and card draws to advance the gameplay).  While it is true randomness arises in many aspects of Armello, I prefer to focus on my reactions to random events as a test of my adaptability.  Flexibility as a strategy as it were.  Is your current approach to victory not panning out?  Switch to another.   Is the leader offensively equipped?  Play defense or throw the King's guards at him by placing a bounty on his head.  You can be combative or stealthy, both are viable.  To be sure, the RNG monster plays no favorites, and I've won games with last minute, low probability strategies that were just as sweet when pulled off as longer, well-planned campaigns.   The good player will embrace randomness as a character on the board and remain open to varying their playstyle in response.To sum up Armello is an outstanding game, not just an outstanding game of its type.  I do not consider myself a rabid fan of digital board/card games but this one won me over with its quality and execution."
