76561198130948719,Recommended,290340,34463266,Posted: 24 August,all,Gamboleer,"HARDWARE: Win 10, i5 3570, GTX 1070. No performance issues, no crashes.I had this on my Wish List, tried it during the free play days, then bought the base game on sale for a little over $10.It's a reasonably fun board game solo, but the singleplayer is probably more useful for learning how the various pieces (avatar abilities, perils, gear, cards, etc) interact as well as doing some limited leveling of the same to learn good strategy so you can survive in multiplayer.Matches have a finite time span of about an hour, as they last a set number of turns, and there are timers (which can be turned down or off in single player) to keep turns moving. The game is turn-based, but there is also a real-time aspect because you can play your cards at any time (subject to card-specific restrictions and available resources) when it's not your turn -- you could, for example, watch two other players fighting and then finish off the winner from a distance with one of your spells. In addition to the player-versus player, the game mechanics also encourage occasional, temporary alliances, some of which are parasitic in nature.Multiplayer allows the inviting of friends and automated matchmaking with strangers. Match sizes are set at 4; it doesn't appear you can do two players and two AI in multiplayer (someone correct me in comments if I'm wrong, please), and there is no local multiplayer. I would like to see these features so I can play a more casual game with a single friend.Production values are top-notch. I did notice a few grammatical and punctuation errors, but nothing horrible.I'd love to see this as a boxed game."
